<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MENA Conference Supports Land-for-Peace Formula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Attendants at the fourth Middle
East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference today expressed
their commitment to the Mideast peace based on the land-for-peace
formula.
</P>
<P>
The stand was contained in the Doha Declaration released at
the closing session of the conference despite strong opposition
from the Israeli delegation.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also called on all parties involved in the
Middle East peace process to keep their commitments to the
already signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The delegates, it said, expressed "grave concern" over the hard
economic situation in the Palestinian self-rule areas caused by
Israeli security closure and called for immediate removal of such
measures.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing ceremony, Qatari Foreign Minister Hamad
Bin Jassim Bin Jabir al-Thani said that "no balanced regional
economic cooperation can be achieved without having a just and
comprehensive peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
On regional economic cooperation, the declaration said some
reform measures like privatization, structural adjustment and
removal of trade barriers have enhanced the region's economic
potentials.
</P>
<P>
The delegates have expressed their desire to encourage the
continuation of the building up of regional institutions like the
Middle East-North Africa Bank for Economic Cooperation and
Development, according to the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of this bank was decided at the previous
conferences, but the initial funding shared by the United States
and other western powers has been delayed.
</P>
<P>
Al-Thani said the conference is a success with some 2,000
people's presence, including 850 foreign business
representatives, from 65 countries.
</P>
<P>
But observers here noted that the actual political
representation is at the lowest level since the MENA conference
was initiated in 1994, because of a massive Arab boycott.
</P>
<P>
A dozen Arab countries, including Egypt, Syria, Saudi Arabia
and the Palestinians, have refused to send political delegations
to the Arab-Israeli conference in protest against Israeli hardline
policy in the deadlocked peace process. Most of those which did
attend were represented only by senior official.
</P>
<P>
But the adverse atmosphere has been offset a bit by an active
participation of the businessmen. The host Qatar has garnered
investment and trade deals worth 4.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The host of next MENA conference will be decided by the World
Economic Forum, which is the convener of the MENA, in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
