<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Wants to Keep Chubais in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
will not remove first Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
Anatoly Chubais from his post, said Itar-Tass news agency today.
</P>
<P>
"The president considered all the economic, financial and
investment consequences of such a resignation," presidential press
secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky told a briefing here.
</P>
<P>
Chubais tendered his resignation for alleged involvement in a
scandal over a book about privatization in Russia. It was reported
that each author of the unpublished book received a fee of 90,000
U.S. dollars, which stirred up a major political scandal.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky suggested that the left-wing opposition in the
State Duma "cool down".
</P>
<P>
The book's co-authors were Maxim Boiko, Deputy Prime Minister
and head of the Ministry for the Management of State Property;
Pyotr Mostovoy, head of the Federal Bankrupcy Agency; and
Alexander Kazakov, First Deputy Chief of Staff of the President.
All of them, except Chubais, have been fired by Yeltsin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
