<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Official Calls for Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and Mozambique should
work together in Malaria control programs to erase the disease in
common border areas, a senior Mozambican health official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Health Director Alexander Manguele said there is need for the two
countries to cooperate in fighting malaria to secure more
success in the anti-malaria campaigns of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
''It is good for the neighbouring countries to engage in technical
discussions involving professionals to map out strategies of how best
we can control the malaria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Manguele said like Zimbabwe, Mozambique had also embarked on a
veccontrol program in its peri-urban and rural areas as well as
shanty towns which are the malaria high risk areas.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique and Angola have the highest malaria related death rates
in the Southern Africa Development Community region.
</P>
<P>
However, Mozambique is aiming at significantly reducing the
malaria death rate by the end of the century through an effective
malaria awareness campaign which had already been launched,
ther Mozambican official said.
</P>
<P>
Manguele said since the end of the civil war in 1992, the
government had implemented an accelerated reconstruction program
for the health sector which had seen most Mozambicans getting access
to health services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
