<HEADLINE> London Sees Largest Development Boom Since 80s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 18 (Xinhua) - Investment of 5.6 billion pounds
(8.96 billion US dollars) in arts, heritage, sports and leisure
projects in London before the Millennium was revealed by Secretary
of State for Culture Chris Smith here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching of an updated report "London - the
Millennium City II", Smith said: "London's leisure industries are
at the heart of what makes it a world-class city."
</P>
<P>
"They make a major contribution to the economy of London and to
the quality of life of Londoners as well as millions of visitors,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The report tracks and costs the major London Lottery and
leisure projects, then takes a wider look at significant
commercial and residential developments, the hotel market and
expanding sectors, such as film, fashion, restaurants and
transport projects.
</P>
<P>
The investment from Lottery and leisure projects alone has
produced the one billion pounds (1.6 billion US dollars) increase,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report is a guide to some of the larger developments and
those with a significant local impact and updates the original,
which was produced in March of this year.
</P>
<P>
The total figure of Lottery and leisure investment has risen
from 4.6 billion pounds (7.36 billion US dollars) to 5.6 billion
pounds (8.96 billion US dollars) in eight months.
</P>
<P>
Praising the contribution by the Lottery and leisure industry,
Smith said that the Lottery is making London not just a world
city but the world city for the new Millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
