<HEADLINE> Intel Plans Price-cutting to Boost Chip Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Intel, the world's Largest
maker of computer chips, is planning the third price-cutting of
its products since last summer, analysts and industry sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
The price levels expected to be introduced on Febuary 1 will be
significantly low. The 233-megahertz (MHz) Pentium II, for
example, will be reduced to 300 U.S. dollars each, said Drew Peck,
analyst from Cowen &AMP; amp Co.
</P>
<P>
Such reductions are aimed at attracting customers to buy its
latest Pentium II computer chips, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the trade publication Computer Retail Week reported
in its on-line edition that Intel was preparing to cut the prices
of large-quantity orders for its 233-MHz Pentium II chip by
roughly one-third.
</P>
<P>
Cited unnamed sources, it reported that in February Intel will
cut prices of its 266-MHz Pentium II to 370 dollars from the
current 520 dollars and its 300-MHz Pentium II from 721 dollars to
520 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new 333-MHz Pentium II will be priced at 705 dollars
each. Two faster versions, the 350-MHz at 840 dollars and the
400-MHz at 980 dollars, are due to ship in April, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
This will be Intel's third major price reduction in the
year. The first price cut in last summer ranged from 30 to 50
percent. The second followed at the end of October when the
markdowns were 13 to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Intel, supplying chips for more than 80 percent personal
computers sold worldwide, has tended to reduce prices of at least
some of its products every quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
