<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Pak Govt-Judiciary Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The confrontation between
the government and the judiciary intensified as Pakistan's
Parliament today adopted the amended contempt law, tending to give
protection to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in the ongoing case of
contempt against him in the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The new law, titled Contempt of Court (Amendment) Act 1997, was
passed by a simple majority in the National Assembly early this
morning and by the Senate later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The law, which provides for an intra-court appeal before a
"larger bench consisting of all the remaining available judges of
the court within the country", has been submitted to President
Farooq Leghari for signing.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic aspect of the law as a provision is that it
would cover the pending cases and shall be applicable even at the
stage of the show-cause notice proceedings.
</P>
<P>
The government's move is seen as an attempt to preempt any
adverse Supreme Court judgment against Prime Minister Sharif and
others in a contempt of court case.
</P>
<P>
The amended law came only one day after Prime Minister Sharif
declined to tender an apology in the Supreme Court in the contempt
of court case against him.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, in an unprecedented move, Nawaz Sharif appeared
personally in the Supreme Court and denied the allegations that he
committed contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in Pakistan's history that an elected
prime minister appeared before the apex court.
</P>
<P>
"I have neither committed contempt of court, nor do I intend to
do that," Sharif said in his written reply to the show-cause
notice issued by the Supreme Court in the contempt of court case.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N) led by Sharif and its
allied parties, which came to power in February this year, enjoy a
favorable majority in both the National Assembly and the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
