<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Hikes in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year
inflation rose to 16 percent in October underpinned by a 2.1
percentage point increase in food inflation, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Last month the Millers Association of Zimbabwe announced a 36
percent increase in meal-mealie, while the Master Bakers
Association hiked the price of bread by between 7.5 and 10
percent which market annalysts said was some of the contributory
factors to the upward move.
</P>
<P>
There was a down surge in inflation from 18 percent in August
to 14.4 percent in September, a drop that surprised most market
watchers who expected the figure to be much higher following a
spate of administered price increases.
</P>
<P>
The Discount Company of Zimbabwe predicted that the
inflation will end the year pegged at around 19 percent because
of a spate of administered price increases and above inflation
wage settlements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
