<HEADLINE> Mubarak Sacked Interior Minister After Luxor Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today kicked out his interior minister in the aftermath of the
country's most deadly attack on foreign tourists in a southern
tourist city on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential decree published today, Hassan el-Alfy was
replaced by Major General Habib Ibrabim el-Adli, head of the State
Security.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Hamam Atiyeh was named as the new head of the State
Security.
</P>
<P>
El-Alfy, 61, had held the post of the interior minister since
1993 when his predecessor Mohamed Abdel-Halim Moussa conducted
unsuccessful negotiations with the militant groups, which
eventually cost his job.
</P>
<P>
At least 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians were killed
after six Islamic militants fired randomly at groups of tourists
in front of the Hatshepsut Temple in Luxor, about 500 kilometers
south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four were also injured in the fire and the ensuing
shoot-out between the police and the gunmen who were also killed.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, in an inspection tour of Luxor, also criticized the
"laxity of security" for the incident.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group, Egypt's most powerful militant group,
claimed responsibility for Monday's attack.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
