<HEADLINE> World Taekwondo Federation Members Increase to 144 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Taekwondo's world governing
body has increased its members to 144 after seven more national
(regional) organizations were recognized as new members of the
World Taekwondo Federation (WTF) here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the WTF's 13th General Assembly today, membership
applications by the associations of Haiti, Somalia, Zimbabwe,
Jamaica, Dominica, Bahamas and Belize were approved.
</P>
<P>
And as a result of an election today, the leadership of the
organization led by its long-standing President Kim Un Yong of
South Korea remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly confirmed that there will be 100 athletes
participating in the Taekwondo competitions at the Sydney Olympic
Games in 2000. They will vie for the medals at stake for the
eight men's and eight women's categories.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly also came to decisions on the two world
championships next year and in 1999. The Second World Junior
Taekwondo Championships has been awarded to Istanbul, Turkey, with
competitions slated for September 3-6 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
And the 14th Men's and Seventh Women's World Taekwondo
Championships are to be held in Edmonton, Canada, on May 24-30,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly was held prior to the opening here on
Wednesday of the five-day 13th Men's and Sixth Women's World
Championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
