<HEADLINE> Indonesia Eyes South African Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is considering
buying armaments from South Africa, and is interested in the
Rooivalk attack helicopter, the South African Press Association
quoted an Indonesian Embassy spokesman as saying today.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility is being considered, but there is nothing
firm," a Indonesian Embassy spokesman Hadi Martono said.
</P>
<P>
He said his government was shopping around for armaments for
defensive purposes.
</P>
<P>
"From the Indonesian side, we are comparing, we are looking at
whether prices are competitive. My personal opinion is that the
Rooivalk is the most advanced, compared to helicopters from other
countries," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Although Indonesian President Soeharto will visit South
Africa this week, the issue will not be raised in talks with
President Nelson Mandela as issues of this nature were generally
dealt with at ministerial level, South African Foreign Ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto will arrive in Cape town on Thursday morning from
Namibia for a two-day visit and is scheduled to hold talks with
Mandela and his deputy Thabo Mbeki later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Asked during a state visit to Jakarta in July whether South
Africa planned to sell arms to Indonesia, Mandela said: "If it
becomes necessary for us to supply arms for external defense to
Indonesia, we will do so without hesitation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
