<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Iraqi Party Regains Lost Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kurdistan Democratic Party
(KDP), a major northern Iraqi party, recaptured most of the
territory lost to its rivals, according to a written statement
issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The KDP forces gained military success in battles with the
pro-Iranian Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and the Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), the KDP statement said.
</P>
<P>
The KDP forces captured on Monday the border post of Haji
Omran on the Iranian border, reasserting its control over the
entire strategic Hamilton road linking norther Iraq and Iran, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The KDP, allegedly backed by Ankara and Baghdad, started its
counter offensives against the PUK and PKK militants since
November 8, driving them back to the demarcated cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and PKK reportedly joined hands in fighting the KDP
since October 13, capturing some of the territory formerly
controlled by the KDP.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and PUK have been fighting each other for the control
of northern Iraq following the 1990 Gulf War. Their clashes
intensified since mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the United States and Britain had accused the PUK of
provoking the fresh clashes with the KDP, which was denied by the
PUK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
