<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KDP Regains Positions From Rival Party in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kurdistan Democratic Party
(KDP), a major northern Iraqi party, recaptured most of the
territory lost to its rivals, according to a written statement
issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The KDP forces gained military success in battles with the
pro-Iranian Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and the Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), the KDP statement said.
</P>
<P>
The KDP forces captured on Monday the border post of Haji
Omran on the Iranian border, reasserting its control over the
entire strategic Hamilton road linking norther Iraq and Iran, it
added.
</P>
<P>
It said that the KDP forces, allegedly backed by Ankara
and Baghdad, started its counter offensives against the PUK and
PKK militants since November 8, driving them back to the
demarcated cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and PKK reportedly joined hands in fighting the
KDP since October 13, capturing some of the territory formerly
controlled by the KDP.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and PUK have been fighting each other for the
control of northern Iraq following the 1990 Gulf War. Their
clashes intensified since Mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the United States and Britain had accused the PUK
of provoking the fresh clashes with the KDP, which was denied
by the PUK.
</P>
<P>
The central government of Iraq had been deprived of control
over the northern part of the country since the Gulf war in 1990
by the allied forces led by the United States. A no-fly zone was
set up there and the Iraqi, Iranian and Turkish rebels had been
operating in the area against their respective governments under
the umbrella of the allied forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
