<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK NHS Waiting List Reaches Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of patients in
Britain waiting to be admitted to a National Health Service (NHS)
hospital reached 1,207,500 at the end of September, an all time
record, according to official figures today.
</P>
<P>
Department of Health figures showed that 818 patients had been
waiting longer than the 18-month Patient's Charter guaranteed
period.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Frank Dobson said that he was setting up a new
task-force to cut waiting lists and the government was committed to
tackling the problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a survey published today by the NHS Confederation
showed that 55 percent of Britain's 120 health authorities predict
they will be in debt by April next year.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of those expecting an overspend are considering
cutting services, and ward closures are likely in one in five
hospitals while almost 60 percent plan to postpone or cancel
routine operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Central Bank Under Fire Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The move by the Reserve Bank,
Zimbabwe's central bank, to increase the rediscount rate in a bid
to reverse the recent slide in the Zimbabwe Dollar will throw
off the track efforts to achieve macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
This was warned today by Zimbabwean economic commentators, who
said Monday's hike of the rediscount rate, the rate at which
banks borrow money from the central bank, did not solve
fundamental macro-economic problems and was only a stop-gap
measure.
</P>
<P>
"All that we have been trying to do to achieve macro-economic
stability will no longer be attainable," Chief Economist of
Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce John Makamure said.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to save the Zimbabwe Dollar which plunged to an all
time low last week under the heavy pressure from import demand, the
Reserve Bank increased the rediscount rate by three percent from
25.5 to 28.5 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Dollar was trading between 19 and 25 Dollars to the U.S.
Dollar after speculations that the Reserve Bank did not have
sufficient foreign currency reserves to finance import
obligations.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank quickly intervened and pumped in some 20
million U.S. Dollars to support the Zimbabwe Dollar which is now
trading at between 13 and 14 Dollars to the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Makamure said while in the short-term the central bank's move
would help arrest the current slide of the local currency, in the
long run the problem might recur.
</P>
<P>
"They are not addressing fundamental problems because they are
only concerned with checking the high import demand," he said,
adding that investor confidence would be further eroded.
</P>
<P>
President of the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Jonee
Blanchfield said, "for as long as the budget deficit and
inflation remain high, the problems of depreciation of the
currency will continue to haunt the economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Ministers Approve Measures Addressing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Delegates including transport
and environment ministers from 40 European countries have agreed
on measures addressing environmental problems caused by transport.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued here today by the United
Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE), the delegates
adopted a political Declaration and a Program of Joint Action at
the end of a three-day meeting held last week in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
The declaration and the program provide a comprehensive set of
strategies and measures to cope with the environmental problems
caused by transport.
</P>
<P>
"What makes this conference so special is that transport
ministers and environment ministers have met for the first time at
the international level and come to the same conclusion: it cannot
go on like this," stressed Yves Berthelot, UN/ECE Executive
Secretary.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, a number of UN/ECE member countries
signed two international legally binding instruments in the field
of transport also aimed at improving its environmental
performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
