<HEADLINE> Former S. African President to Be Subpoenaed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P W Botha will be subpoenaed again to testify at the
next round of hearings on the role of the former State Security
Council, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The subpoena is likely to be delivered this afternoon, SAPA
said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted sources from the Truth and Reconcilidation
Commission as saying that the only thing that is uncertain is
whether the hearings will be held in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokeswoman Christelle Terreblanche said former
Defense Minister Magnus Malan and former Head of the Intelligence
Service, Neil Barnard, would also appear at the hearings one day
before Botha's supposed testimony on December 5.
</P>
<P>
Botha was subpoenaed at the end of September to appear before
the Truth and Reconciliation Commission at the first round of
hearings in Johannesburg in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
But his testimony was postponed on the grounds of ill health.
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu then decided to hold the second round
in George, Western Cape, a place close to Botha's retirement
home.
</P>
<P>
But Botha said at the weekend in an interview with an
Afrikaans newspaper that he would rather be taken to court and
charged than appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
An angry Tutu said Monday that the hearing will continue and
that if Botha is not willing to attend, the commission's founding
act would come into play.
</P>
<P>
The Promotion of National Unity and Reconciliation Act
provides for a fine, a two-year jail term or both if a person
refuses to obey a subpoena without sufficient causes.
</P>
<P>
Botha said he would not apologize for the role of his
government in the apartheid era and that nor would he apply for
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the TRC, a special court set up to heal the wounds
of apartheid, saying that it has gradually been turned into a
revenge camp against the Afrikaner.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is simply that the commission does not bring
reconciliation, but is trying to tear the Afrikaner and the South
African nation apart," he said in the newspaper interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
