<HEADLINE> US Envoy Upset Over No Progress in Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States ambassador
to Angola Donald Steinberg said here today that he felt
disappointed over the failure to achieve progress in the Angolan
peace process recently.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Angolan parliament Speaker Roberto da Almeida,
Steinberg told reporters that the opposition Nation Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has refused to cooperate with
the Angolan government in re-establishing local government organs
in the areas under its control and transforming its radio station
into a non-partisan commercial one since the UN sanctions against
it took effect on October 30.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the UNITA also suspended the disbandment
of its remaining troops, thus no progress has been made in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the United Nations will hold a informal
meeting this week to discuss the situation in Angola and at the
meeting the UN special representative Blondin Beye will present a
report on the present situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
New sanction measures are likely to be taken at the meeting,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The American envoy urged the UNITA to take concrete measures
to implement the Lusaka peace agreement signed in 1994. 
</P>
