<HEADLINE> Stone Age Tools Discovered in Northern Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists from the
British Research Institute have discovered Stone Age tools in
Ethiopia's northern highland, about five kms from the historic
Axum Town.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ethiopian News Agency today quoted David
Philipson, Director of the Eastern Africa Archaeological Eesearch
project, as saying that the findings have given new incitements
into Stone Age settlements in Ethiopia, which, according to
archaeological discoveries so far, are limited to the Rift Valley
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The director said the tools, found by Laurel Philipson, a
member of the team executing the project, include mortars,
crushers and knives and are between 15-25 centimeters long.
</P>
<P>
Earlier searches near Axum and Shire, northern Tigray State of
Ethiopia, have rendered similar tools used during the Middle
Ages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
