<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Vital to Southern Africa: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The private sector will
play an important part in the future development of southern
Africa, a senior official of Southern African Development
Community (SADC) said in Gaborone, Botswana today.
</P>
<P>
"We are opening up to the private sector and this process is
irreversible," Kaire Mbuende, SADC Executive Secretary, told the
southern African trade and investment summit, which is organized
by the International Herald Tribune.
</P>
<P>
"This conference illustrates the strong desire of this region
to intensify economic cooperation with the private sector. Our
program of action is geared towards equity and growth, with a
very strong bias towards the private sector as the engine of
growth," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of regional trade, he said, the SADC is the most
integrated and advanced economic bloc in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"For a group of developing countries that have emerged from
civil strife and political instability, this indeed a great
achievement," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Intra-SADC trade is about 22 percent of total SADC trade. Out
of this, it is estimated that seven billion U.S. Dollars worth of
trade is transacted in goods with tariffs ranging between zero to
five percent.
</P>
<P>
"Seventy percent of the trade is taking place under very low
tariff," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that the importance for a SADC free
trade area is not only in the expansion of intra-SADC trade
flows, but also in its potential to stimulate domestic,
cross-border and foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
"The object of SADC is to have balanced trade among its
members states. This can only be achieved if trade in the region
is completely liberalized and the countries produce goods and
services according to their comparative advantages," the SADC
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Hopes for Diplomatic Way Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today again expressed
welcome to efforts to seek a diplomatic solution to the present
crisis, but stressed its demands for the United Nations should be
met "in totality."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al Sahhaf told a news
briefing this afternoon that Iraq has presented eight demands to
the U.N., which constitute a plan for solving the standoff over
weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
He said Baghdad asked for the implementation of paragraph 22 of
the U.N. resolution 687 to lift the seven-year-old sanctions
against Iraq and the restructuring of the U.N. arms monitoring
group "in a balanced way."
</P>
<P>
That means the U.N. commission overseeing Iraq's disarmament
would have more members of all nationalities rather than American
citizens who he accused of implementing U.S. hostile policies
against Iraq, and carry out its mission in a "fair, objective and
scientific way," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf challenged the U.S. to accept the formation of a
committee comprises of representatives of five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council and any number of neutral countries
to come to Iraq to check and verify all American allegations that
Iraq is hiding secretive weapons development programs.
</P>
<P>
He called the allegations "false" and "baseless" which were
aimed at misinforming and deceiving the world public.
</P>
<P>
He attacked U.S. President Bill Clinton for failing to
recognize that 400 Iraqi children died daily because of
U.N. sanctions and U.S. effort to prevent the Security Council
from fulfilling obligations toward Iraq - lifting sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He brushed aside the reported offer by the U.S. to broaden the
"oil-for-food" program as an incentive for Baghdad to back off,
saying it is irrelevant to a political or diplomatic way out.
</P>
<P>
The program "has nothing to do with it" and therefore can not
be part of a political package, he said. He also pointed out that
the U.S. wants to play up the "temporary measure" for a "diversion
from the real target" of lifting sanctions.
</P>
<P>
However, he softened his tone by saying "We encourage dialogue
between Iraq and the United States." 
</P>
</TEXT>
