<P>
"On behalf of the Israeli people, I express my sympathy
and condolences to those foreign tourists and Egyptians who have
been killed in the Luxor shooting, and hope this incident
will not affect the cooperation in tourism between our two
countries," Weizman told Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that gunmen disguised as policemen stormed
the Egypt's renowed Pharaonic temple Hatshepsut outside Luxor on
Monday, killing at least 77 people, most of them were
foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who was in Los
Angeles on Monday, also telephoned Mubarak as soon as he
heard the news to express condolences, the Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Foreign Minister David
Levy, also sent messages of condolences to their Egyptian
counterparts expressing their regrets.
</P>
<P>
Local residents here said that they were shocked at the
Luxor shooting, urging the Egyptian government to take tough
actions against those who behind it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
