<HEADLINE> UK Says UN Arms Inspection Composition Could be Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The British government
indicated today that it might agree to change the composition of
the UN arms inspection team, but refuse to discuss the issue with
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The London government rejected Monday an Iraqi compromise
proposal of readmitting American arms inspectors, under which the
Iraqis insisted on equal representation on the arms inspection
teams to all five permanent Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
Britain's stance remains tough today with a government official
reported as saying: "We will not negotiate with Iraq on the
composition of UNSCOM (the UN Special Commission on Iraq)."
</P>
<P>
However, the official gave some indication of making
concessions by saying: "We have no problem if that mix (of the
inspetion teams) were to increase and if an individual country
increased its numbers (within UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
"This would be no problem for Britain as far as United Nations
operations go," he added.
</P>
<P>
A British intelligence assessment was quoted by the Reuters as
saying today that Iraq could make some chemical and biological
weapons "in a matter of months" if the UN arms inspection teams
were removed "for a sustained period". 
</P>
</TEXT>
