<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps Lusaka Improve Basic Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and the Irish Aid will provide Lusaka with a total
of 1.368 million U.S. Dollars to help the capital Lusaka improve
its basic services.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed here today by the UNDP, the Irish
Aid and the Zambian government, the UNDP promises to give 700,000
Dollars, and the Irish Aid 668,000 Dollars while the government
will allocate 172,000 Dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
Acting Permanent Secretary for the Ministry of Finance and
Economic Planning Hkonga Mwaba said at the signing ceremony that
there has been a rapid degradation of Zambia's urban environment
due to unsustainable development patterns.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Zambian cities especially Lusaka have failed to cope
with the growing population's demand for basic services such as clean
water supply and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade and more, the population of Lusaka has
increased by at least fourfold, from about half a million to
well over two million.
</P>
<P>
Mwaba called on the Lusaka City Council to include poverty
eradication in the sustainable Lusaka program.
</P>
<P>
He said the high levels of poverty in the city contribute to
environmental degradation and that the two should be addressed at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
UNDP acting resident representative Omoefe Oyaide said the UNDP is
committed to supporting Zambia in its effort to eradicate environment
degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
