<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Massacre in Southern Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today strongly condemns
the Monday massacre in southern Egypt, in which 77 tourists were
killed, including 73 foreigners, Jordan's official news agency
Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
In a cable of condolence to his Egyptian counterpart Kamal
el-Ganzouri, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali said
today that such a criminal act ran contrary to Arab and Islamic
traditions and should be strongly condemned.
</P>
<P>
Majali called for efforts at regional and international levels
to put an end to terrorist acts wherever they came from and
whoever stood behind them.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries should seek closer cooperation and the
international community should offer more help for the Arab
countries in combating terrorist acts, he added in his cable.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan, who is now in the United States, made a
phone call Monday to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
expressed condolence over the death of Egyptians and foreign
tourists in the massacre.
</P>
<P>
The king expressed Jordan's support for the Egyptian
government and people in face of such acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Jordanian Minister of State for Information
Affairs Samir Mutawe said in an official statement that "our
position on these criminal acts is crystal clear. We condemn such
acts of violence and terrorism regardless of their source and
who stands behind them."
</P>
<P>
"We in Jordan support the Egyptian position vis-a-vis such
acts of violence and express our deep condolences to the
bereaved families and wish those injured a speedy recovery," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe added that these criminal acts, which caused human and
material losses, sabotage the aspirations of the people in the
region towards stability and peace.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayaz Tarawneh called his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa Monday and condemned the massacre.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been enjoying a friendly relationship with Egypt.
It unilaterally recognized Egypt in September 1984, becoming the
first Arab state to do so after most Arab League members cut
their ties with Cairo in 1979 to protest the Israeli-Egyptian
peace treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
