<HEADLINE> N. Cyprus Leader Sticks to "Two States" Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Northern Cyprus Leader Rauf
Denktas said today that talks between the two communities on the
island should be based on "two states" principle.
</P>
<P>
Denktas stated: "negotiations may foresee federation, but we
will sit at the negotiation table representing a state no mater
the Greek Cypriot side recognizes us or not", according to a
report of Turkey's Anatolia News Agency from Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to questions regarding the statement of
U.S. president's Special Envoy to Cyprus Richard Holbrooke, who
claimed that the two leaders favored federation on the island,
Denktas pointed out, "the main thing of the 'Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus' and its existence, yet its recognition depends
on the political will of other countries."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Greek Cypriot side can not join European
Union (EU) without Turkish Cypriots, adding that firstly the
principles which were put forward by 1960 Treaties should be
applied.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been split into a Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and a Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 and Turkey has
since maintained 35,000-strong troops in the northern third.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 the breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
