<HEADLINE> UNHCR Provides Relief for Somali Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) today provided 50,000 U.S.
Dollars and 2,000 blankets for emergency distribution to flood
victims in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here today, UNHCR said that it is
also preparing to release up to 78 tons of high protein biscuits
from its emergency stockpile to meet immediate food needs of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the record-breaking flooding in southern
Somalia's Juba and Shabelle valley regions had killed more than
2,000 people and displaced 200,000 more.
</P>
<P>
Yvette Stevens, UNHCR representative for Kenya and Somalia
noted that "it will be a great tragedy if, due to a lack of
funds, aid arrives too late to prevent even more massive
population displacements."
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies operating in the country pointed out that
local crop production in southern Somalia had been completely
ruined by floods.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains which started to pour down in southern
Somalia in mid-October have cause the 600-kilometer-long Juba
River to burst its embankments in several locations.
</P>
<P>
The expected January harvest is to be virtual failure in many
southern areas due to heavy rains and flooding, according to a
report issued by the World Food Program (WFP) last week.
</P>
<P>
The report said at least 200,000 Somalis im the south were
facing severe food shortage which could be as much as 20,000 to
30,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
