<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Single Digit Inflation Predicted in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) predicted today
that all SADC member states would have single digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that by the turn of the century, all the SADC
member states will have inflation rates below 10 percent provided
present prudent fiscal and monetary discipline is maintained,"
Kaire Mbuende, SADC executive secretary said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the Southern African Trade and
Investment Summit, which is discussing the future of the SADC
region in Gaborone, Botswana. The conference will run till
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, Mbuende said, the 14 SADC member countries
would also have their fiscal deficit reduced to below six
percent.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reason for the prediction, Mbuende said,
"fiscal deficits have been reduced to six percent of gross
domestic product in 1995 in most of the SADC countries.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of present trends, it is expected that for
1996/97 the level of fiscal deficits in SADC member states will
be lower than in 1995/96."
</P>
<P>
On the economic performance of the SADC countries, Mbuende
said there had been a steady rise in the average growth in the
GDP from 3.0 percent in 1994 to 3.7 percent in 1995 and 4.1
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"With this trend, I expect that growth in GDP will rise to 4.5
percent in 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
SADC, established in 1992, is a regional organization to
develop regional economy and to promote free trade within its
framework.
</P>
<P>
SADC member states are Angola, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia, South
Africa, Mauritius, Seychelles and the Democratic Republic of
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
