<HEADLINE> Annan Is Optimistic About Diplomatic Solution to Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today expressed optimism over diplomatic solution to
the latest crisis over Iraqi weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters about whether Russia had a plan to solve the
crisis, Annan said Russia had tried very hard to diffuse the
situation and he was optimistic about it.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and Russian
leaders were discussing proposals in Moscow now, and he hoped
there would be results.
</P>
<P>
UN spokesman Eckhard Fred said in today's briefing that
governments were consulting with each other over the diplomatic
solution to the crisis and results could be expected later this
week.
</P>
<P>
He also told reporters that Iraqi Government had sent a letter
to the Secretary-General, in which it proposed a second meeting
between the UN chief and its deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Fred said the letter had just arrived and the Secretary-General
had not responded to it.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis over Iraqi arms inspection began on October
29 when Iraqi government announced its decision to expel American
arms inspectors working for the United Nations and shoot down
American U-2 planes flying for the United Nations. The inspectors
are part of the teams monitoring Iraqi compliance with the United
Nations resolutions demanding that Iraq destroy all its weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, Chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission, order to withdraw most of the arms inspectors from
Iraq the following day. 
</P>
