<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Foils Coup Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has aborted a coup led by some soldiers aimed at putting an
end to the on-going peace process in that country.
</P>
<P>
About 80 soldiers of the armed forces of Sierra Leone and
fighters of the ex-rebel Revolutionary United Front have been
arrested, Col. Godwin Ugbo, spokesman of Nigeria's defense
headquarters, said here today.
</P>
<P>
The abortive coup, confirmed by a report of the British
Broadcasting Corporation, was led by a group of soldiers,
including Steve Bio, brother of a former defense minister, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the coup which took place on Monday is to
overthrow the rule of Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who came to power
after ousting the legitimate government of President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah in a coup on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
The coupists wanted to maintain military rule in the country
because Koroma has promised to hand over power to President
Kabbah in April next year, said Ugbo, who is also director of the
defense information department.
</P>
<P>
The frustration of the fresh coup, according to observers,
will help promote the peace process in Sierra Leone although the
Koroma-led junta differs with west African countries over whether
the national army would be disarmed along with other combatants
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace accord the junta signed in Conakry,
Guinea last month, all the people with guns across Sierra Leone
should be disarmed and demobilized.
</P>
<P>
But during the talks to work out modalities for implementing
the peace plan earlier this month, the junta refused to do so,
arguing that the armed forces could not be disarmed because it
was set up by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
However, the junta has begun to disarm child soldiers which
are estimated at about 5,000 throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
