<HEADLINE> Russian, U.S. FBI Officials Discuss Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia wasts closer and more
active cooperation with U.S. special services, Russian Security
Council Secretary Ivan Rybkin stated at a meeting today with
visiting FBI Director Louis Freeh, according to the Interfax news
service.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin said that the Russian president encourages cooperation
with foreign law enforcement agencies in fighting crime. Working
contacts between Russian and U.S. special services will show that
the relations between the two countries have matured, the secretary
said.
</P>
<P>
Freeh, in his part, said that the level of cooperation between
U.S. and Russian law enforcement agencies in fighting crime and
money laundering and in training personnel that has been
established since his first visit to Moscow three years ago is not
bad.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also focused on fighting against international
terrorism, the Security Council press service said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) Director Nikolai
Kovalyov and Freeh today also discussed cooperation in fighting
international organized crime, international terrorism and drug
trafficking at a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two men agreed that their agencies had reached a high level
of mutual understanding and cooperation but could do more in this
field.
</P>
<P>
The FBI director arrived in Moscow on Tuesday for a four-day
visit. He is expected to have serious talks with Russian
Vice-Premier and Minister of Interior Anatoly Kulikov. 
</P>
