<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Disarm Child Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's military junta
has started identifying and registering the country's estimated
5,000 child soldiers as a preparation to disarm them in December.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted the junta's Social Welfare
Minister Major Kula Samba as saying that identification and
registration work started Monday in regional capitals including
Bo, Kenema, Makeni and other towns.
</P>
<P>
The move was in the spirit of the Conakry agreement signed
last Month in Guinea between the junta and the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provided that all soldiers in Sierra Leone, no
matter which faction they belong to, will be disarmed starting
from December, as the first step toward the restoration of
elected civilian President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah and his government were overthrown by a sector of the
country's armed forces on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Samba, child soldiers were employed by the
country's army, the Revolutionary United Front rebels, the
Kamajors traditional hunters and other militia groups.
</P>
<P>
To implement the Conakry agreement, the ECOWAS peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) has held several talks with the Sierra Leonean
junta led by Major Paul Johnny Koroma.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the junta has agreed to disarm all the
militia groups but insisted the army could not be disarmed,
because it is the national army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
