<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Create More Jobs Via Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
pronounced that environmental protection can contribute to job
creation among European Union member states.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the European summit on employment, the
commission, the executive body of the 15-nation union, adopted a
communication on environment and employment.
</P>
<P>
The communication was jointly presented by commissioners Ritt
Bjerregaard and Padraig Flynn, in charge of environment and
employment respectively.
</P>
<P>
The commission document announces a concrete agenda for
building a sustainable Europe by achieving a competitive economy
combined with less environmental degradation, improved resource
efficiency of energy and raw materials, and higher employment
rates.
</P>
<P>
Upon adoption, Commissioner Bjerregaard said: "It is now clear
that environment and employment are mutually compatible and if the
two policy areas give more attention to each other, we will obtain
greater results."
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.5 million people in the union now work in
environment-related jobs, according to the Employment Europe
Report 1997. Of the total, about 2 million deal with clean
technologies, renewable energy, waste recycling, nature and
landscape protection and ecological renovation of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The rest is found in the so-called eco-businesses which produce
technologies, goods and services to measure, prevent, limit or
correct environmental damage to water, air and soil, as well as
problems related to waste, noise and eco-system.
</P>
<P>
"A greater use of renewable energy could generate half a
million of jobs by 2010 while in urban areas thousands of jobs can
be created through investments in renovation of houses and in
public transport, improving considerably the quality of life and
of the environment," added Bjerregaard.
</P>
<P>
High levels of unemployment now go together with environmental
degradation caused by specific sectors such as industry,
transport, energy, agriculture and consumption pattern.
</P>
<P>
The "underuse" of labor resources and the "overuse" of
environmental resources must be reversed, said the communication.
</P>
<P>
European Union-wide, unemployment rate now stands at 10.6
percent while Luxembourg, now serving the six-month rotating
presidency of the union, aspires to cope with the unemployment
issue within its tenure.
</P>
<P>
The two-day employment summit is slated for Thursday and Friday
in Luxembourg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
