<HEADLINE> U-2 Resumes flight over Iraq without Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A U-2 spy plane resumed its
mission for U.N. weapons inspections by flying over Iraq on
Tuesday without incident, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
"The U-2 has completed its UNSCOM (U.N. Special commission)
mission over Iraq without incident. The plane is back out of
Iraqi territory," Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
It has been the second U-2 flight in eight days since Iraq
threatened to shoot down any U-2 planes flying over its
territorial at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
The U-2 spy plane, based in Saudi Arabia, flew at an attitude
of up to 70,000 feet and took extremely clear photographs of the
ground. "It's flown and everything went well," a Pentagon
official said. And another official said Iraq made no attempt to
interfere with the U-2. 
</P>
