<HEADLINE> Floods Claim 297 Lives in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Mohammed Mealin, head of
Ethiopia's eastern Somali State said today that the floods have
so far claimed 297 lives in the state.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted him as telling the press in
Jijiga, capital city of the Somali State, that over 12,000
domestic animals were killed and crops on 30,000 hectares of land
as well as 4,254 residential houses were also destroyed by the
floods.
</P>
<P>
Some 65,000 people have been displaced due to the flooding, he
added.
</P>
<P>
A consignment of food, shelter and clothing provided by the
Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Commission and the Ethiopian
Red Cross Society has been airlifted to the affected areas,
Mealin said, adding that five additional helicopters are needed
to supply relief goods to flood victims in the state.
</P>
<P>
Operations are still underway to rescue people surrounded by
water in Mustahel locality, Mealin noted.
</P>
<P>
He also called on international and local donor agencies to
extend assistance to mitigate transport problem in the affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
Some areas of the Ethiopia's Somali State were flooded as a
result of the overflowing of the Wabe Shabelle river following
recent heavy rains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
