<HEADLINE> Turkey's RP Leader Defends against Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Islamist Welfare Party
(RP) Chairman Necmettin Erbakan said here today that the attempt
to close his party opposed procedural law.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark while delivering a verbal defense in the
case filed by High Appeals Court Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas for
closure of his party.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan believed that Savas' filing the case on grounds of RP's
violation of articles 68 and 69 of the Constitution while failing
to pinpointing any breach of the Political Parties Law was
against procedural law.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Erbakan repeated his opinion that the case must be
dismissed from the point of view of procedure.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan's submission of his verbal defense was done at a
hearing here, which was closed to press.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan was expected to deliver the verbal defense on November
11. He requested an additional period of 20 days to prepare his
verbal defense in the closure case, but was granted only a week.
</P>
<P>
Savas filed the case with the Constitutional Court in May
demanding the RP be shut down on the grounds of its support for
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkey's Party Law, Erbakan and other senior RP
officials will be banned from engaging in politics for at least
five years if the party is outlawed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
