<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Pick Up Slightly in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. consumer prices
moved up a modest 0.2 percent in October, continuing the steady
trend of inflation rate of the previous three months, the Labor
Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
For the first 10 months of 1997, Consumer Price Index filed by
the Department has risen at an annual rate of just 1.8 percent as
compared to a 3.3 percent increase during 1996.
</P>
<P>
While the inflation figures were in line with expectations, a
separate report on business inventories was a bit stronger than
anticipated, pushing bond market yields higher from nearly a
two-year low. Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds, a barometer for
long-term borrowing costs, rose to 6.07 percent this morning from
late Monday's level of 6.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said business inventories grew 0.7
percent in September after much smaller gains of 0.2 percent in
July and 0.1 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
But the growth was outpaced by sales, which jumped 1.3 percent
after a drop of 0.6 percent a month earlier. That resulted in an
inventory-to-sales ratio of just 1.36.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices fell across the board, except for a 2.4 percent
increase for natural gas. The 0.1 percent overall increase was the
smallest since a 0.1 percent dip in July. Prices had risen 1.7
percent in August and 1.3 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline costs, which had jumped 5.4 percent in August and 1.8
percent in September, were down 0.6 percent. Prices for
electricity and fuel oil both declined 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food costs also remained contained, advancing 0.2 percent after
a 0.1 percent gain a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Price increases in most other categories also remained modest.
</P>
<P>
Although housing costs rose 0.3 percent, clothing, medical care
and transportation costs each inched up just 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices of new cars actually fell 0.3 percent despite the
beginning of the new model year. Auto finance charges were down
0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent increase in food prices was due largely to a
1.5 percent jump in the cost of dairy products, steepest since a
1.8 percent advance a year ago.
</P>
<P>
But prices for beef were down 0.6 percent; for pork, down 0.4
percent, and for poultry, down 0.8 percent. Fresh vegetable costs
were unchanged, but fruit prices rose 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Coffee prices, which had risen during much of the year, were
down 1.8 percent. It was the biggest drop since they fell 2.1
percent in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Airline fares shot up 3.8 percent on top of a 2.1 percent jump
in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
