<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders More Warplanes to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
today ordered additional U.S. warplanes to the Gulf as a beefing
up of American forces in the region in an attempt to pressure Iraq
to reverse its decision of expulsion of U.S. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by National Security adviser Samuel
Berger right after Clinton's meeting with his senior military and
diplomatic advisors at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials said Clinton had been asked by the
Pentagon to send bombers and F-117 stealth fighters to the Gulf
after receiving diplomatic permission from some Arab states in the
region to increase pressure on Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
There is no immediate indication where the additional Air Force
planes would be based, but the U.S. military already has a potent
force of more than 250 Air Force and Navy airplanes and 22
warships in the Gulf and Red Sea within striking distance of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
About 150 of the planes are in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait and
another 100 on the aircraft carriers Nimitz and George Washington.
</P>
<P>
The George Washington, ordered by Clinton to move to the Gulf
from the Mediterranean last week, is currently moving south in the
Red Sea and will enter the Gulf later this week to join the
Nimitz.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Pentagon said a U-2 spy plane flew over Iraq on
order from the United Nations for weapons inspections. It was the
second flight by the plane in eight days.
</P>
<P>
Iraq did not interfere with the flight as it once vowed to do
so, and the U-2 flew back safely to its air base in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Berger said the beefing up of the American forces in the region
was under consideration for about a week and was not directly
related to the resumption of the U-2 flight today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
