<HEADLINE> Egypt to Take New Security Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today gave instructions forming a committee entrusted with mapping
out a "water-tight" plan for securing the major tourist cities in
the country, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said to newspapers' chief editors accompanying him from
Luxor to Cairo today that the committee will comprise the prime
minister, the defense and interior ministers and the governors of
Aswan, Luxor, Sharm el-Sheikh and Hurghda, Egypt's major tourist
cities, to finalize a plan within 48 to 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
The president visited the latter three cities today, a day
after the country's most deadly terrorist attack took place in
Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Six Islamic militants fired randomly at groups of tourists in
front of the Hatshepsut Temple in Luxor, killing 77 tourists,
including 73 foreigners. Mubarak criticized the "laxity of
security" at the site.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also issued directives today to join the tourism and
antiquities police together under one administration and under one
leadership, to realize efficiency and discipline.
</P>
<P>
The directive came about three months after ex-Minister of
Interior Hassan el-Alfy decided to separate the two departments.
</P>
<P>
In a decree issued earlier today, Mubarak decided to replace
el-Alfy with Major General Habib Ibrabim el-Adli, head of the
State Security.
</P>
<P>
El-Alfy, 61, in the post of the interior minister since 1993,
was reputed for his heavy-handed dealing with the Islamic
militants that have been fighting a five-year war against
Mubarak's secular government.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group, Egypt's most powerful militant group,
claimed responsibility for Monday's attack.  
</P>
</TEXT>
