<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU Agrees on Closer Link with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of the European defense
group Western European Union (WEU) agreed today to forge a closer
link with the European Union (EU) in a bid to enhance its role as
an instrument of European crisis management and as the security
arm of the EU.
</P>
<P>
As the most important step to link the WEU with the EU, WEU
members decided that up from 1999, a country which holds the
rotating presidency of the EU should also take over the presidency
of the WEU provided that it is also a full member of the defense
group.
</P>
<P>
Under such an arrangement, Germany is due to assume the first
double presidency of the two organizations in the first half of
1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the two-day WEU meeting at the eastern
German city of Erfurt, which was attended by foreign and defense
ministers from 28 European states.
</P>
<P>
According to German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, the WEU
meeting also agreed on measures to intensify cooperation with the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), including the
installation of a consultation mechanism in case of a crisis
situation.
</P>
<P>
In Erfurt, ministers also finalized details of setting up a
military committee within the WEU which is to become the
alliance's supreme military authority. A proposal to give the
European Parliament direct control over the WEU had failed to
achieve consensus.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, ministers also decided to expand a WEU mission that
trains police in Albania and to extend its mandate to next spring.
</P>
<P>
WEU General Secretary Jose Cutileiro told reporters today that
the Erfurt meeting had made the WEU politically more reliable and
well prepared for peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted in an interview with the German Thuringer
Allgemeine newspaper that there was still a lack of common defense
policy in Europe. "A common policy in this regard is still far
from being formulated as we wish," he said.
</P>
<P>
The WEU, founded in 1948, now groups almost all EU members
except Austria, Denmark, Finland, Ireland and Sweden, which only
have observer status in the organization.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it has three associated members -- Iceland, Norway
and Turkey -- along with 10 associated partner states in central
and eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
