<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inland-HK Tourism Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The long-term strategy of the
Hong Kong Tourist Administration (HKTA) is to promote cooperation
in tourism between Hong Kong and inland areas.
</P>
<P>
B.Y. Wong, chief Beijing representative for HKTA, said the HK
government organization has introduced a program to promote
cooperation with its counterparts in Beijing, Shanghai, Xi'an and
Guilin. The goal of the program, introduced earlier this month, is
to develop tourism sources in the North American market.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism is a pillar industry in the Hong Kong economy, and the
region has accumulated vast marketing experience. Nonetheless,
limited tourism resources require that we expand cooperation with
inland areas to promote tourism," said Wong.
</P>
<P>
He said various factors will contribute to a projected 10
percent drop in the number of tourists visiting Hong Kong during
1997. However, the industry is expected to regain momentum next
year with a projected growth of some six percent, according to
Wong. "We are fully optimistic about next year," said Wong.
</P>
<P>
He noted that over 1.69 million tourists from inland areas
visited Hong Kong between January-September, with related areas
for the first time emerging as the region's largest source
market. He predicted that a total of 2.4 million inland tourists
will visit Hong Kong during 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The central government has further relaxed its policies, and
we anticipate steady growth in the number of inland visitors
during 1998," said Wong.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA has also introduced a winter tour package offering
preferential terms for inland visitors, including cash vouchers
valued at 7,600 HK dollars for each person. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
