<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, South Korean Win Titles in World Taekwondo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Tamer Abd el Monem
and South Korea's Hae Eun Kang won the first gold medals at the
13th Men's and Sixth Women's Taekwondo World Championships which
opened in the Hong Kong Coliseum here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his second appearance at world championships, Monem, 23,
defeated Frenchman Christophe Negreal 3-1 in the final of the
men's light weight category for the title. Negreal was making his
 world championships debut here.
</P>
<P>
In the women's light weight final, the 21-year-old Kang, also
debutee in the world championships, won over Chinese Taipei's Hung
 Chia-Chun 3-1 for the first gold medal of the women's
categories.
</P>
<P>
Competing in the five-day event are some 600 athletes from 93
countries and regions. This is the largest sporting event Hong
Kong has ever staged and the first world-class event held in Hong
Kong after its take-over by China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
There are eight categories in the men's and women's divisions.
</P>
<P>
Taekwondo will be listed for the first time as an Olympic sport
at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000, with four categories each for
men and women.
</P>
<P>
China has sent a 16-athlete team for the current championships,
 its second appearance at the world taekwondo championships
following the last worlds two years ago in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Li Bo finished in the top eight of the men's light
weight category and his fellow countrywoman Zhang Huijing managed
to the top 16 on the event's opening day today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
