<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President on Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Economic and trade cooperation
between Sri Lanka and China should be further strengthened, Sri
Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga told a senior Chinese
official here this evening.
</P>
<P>
She made this remark while meeting with Chen Muhua, vice
chairperson of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress of China, at her official residence.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade cooperation between the two sides should be
done within the framework of the new economic policies that both
countries have adopted, she said.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga expressed the belief that Chen's visit to her
country will further consolidate the already existing Sino-Sri
Lankan friendship.
</P>
<P>
She asked Chen to convey her greetings to Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and restated her invitation to Jiang to visit Sri
Lanka at a convenient time.
</P>
<P>
Chen extended Jiang's best regards to Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
Chen said Sino-Sri Lankan friendship dates back to ancient
times. Ever since the establishment of the diplomatic ties, the
bilateral relations between the two nations have been developing
well.
</P>
<P>
China treasures its friendly relations with Sri Lanka and is
willing to join hands with Sri Lanka to advance their friendship
and cooperation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chen and her entourage arrived here Monday on a three-day
official goodwill visit to Sri Lanka, the third leg of her South
Asia tour which has taken her to Pakistan and Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
