<HEADLINE> Sino-US Orange Juice Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-US orange juice
production base will be established in Central China's Three
Gorges area, home to the world's largest hydropower project.
</P>
<P>
The US-based Seagrams Co. Ltd. and the Three Gorges
Construction Group signed a contract today calling for the
establishment of a joint research, production, processing and
marketing base.
</P>
<P>
The project will be the second of its king Seagram has
established in China, with the first venture currently under
construction in Beihai, in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, according to Seagrams President Edgar Bronfman.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Three Gorges base will proceed in three
phases.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase, which will be carried out by the Chinese
partner, will involve planting one million orange trees on 3,000
hectares. Seagrams will provide a 10 million U.S. dollars loan for
the initial project.
</P>
<P>
Seagrams will invest an additional 11 million U.S. dollars to
construct an orange technological center to research and develop a
new strain known as the Seagrams Tropicana Sanxia (Three Gorges)
Orange. The company will also provide hybrid saplings free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
The Tropicana Sanxia Juice Processing Facility, the final
phase, will be carried out jointly by the Three Gorges
Construction Group and Tropicana Asia Pacific, a Seagrams
subsidiary. The facility will be constructed at a cost of 15
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two Seagrams projects, which will feature state-of-the-art
technology, are expected to become leading orange production
centers in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Bronfman expressed great interest for further investments in
China, and noted that the company's recent market survey in
Guangzhou and Shanghai revealed a large demand for orange juice.
</P>
<P>
He said Seagrams has already invested over 100 million
U.S. dollars in China's orange industry.
</P>
<P>
The orchard project is expected to employ some 40,000 local
farmers, many of whom were relocated as part of Three Gorges
resettlement program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
