<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea, DPRK Link Flight Control Towers With Phone Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) opened a direct communications
line between their air traffic control towers this morning.
</P>
<P>
The direct phone line is expected to be a prelude to the
opening of DPRK's airspace next April, said the Ministry of
Construction and Transportation.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, South Korea's Taegu control tower
chief talked over the phone with his Pyongyang counterpart for two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will use the telephone line regularly at 10
a.m. everyday to notify each other of flight numbers, plane types,
routes, altitudes and arrival time of planes entering their flight
information region (FIR).
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct communications line between them,
although civilian organizations such as the Red Cross have already
set up communications lines, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Since 1945 when the Korean Peninsula was divided into two,
South Korea and DPRK have been prohibiting each other's national
flag carriers from passing through their air space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
