<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Russia and Iraq have drafted a proposal to end the standoff
between the United States and Saddam Hussein, said Russia's
Foreign Minister, Yevgeny Primakov. He said the plan would allow
the United Nations to carry out weapons inspections, presumably
with the participation of Americans, but that the open-ended
search should be brought to a speedy end.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon offered President Kennedy an extraordinary
variety of dirty tricks designed to sabotage Fidel Castro, newly
declassified documents show. These plans included sophomoric
pranks, such as faking a picture of a fat and debauched Castro to
destroy his image, and murderous plots.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton pressed forward yesterday with
his diplomatic drive to cultivate closer ties with oil-rich former
Soviet republics in Central Asia while trying to prevent Iran from
profiting from the development of the region's vast energy
resources.
</P>
<P>
--The Federal Bureau of Investigation said today that a
16-month probe into the TWA 800 crash had turned up no evidence
that a criminal act brought down the jumbo jet, leaving mechanical
failure as the most likely cause of the 1996 disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton ordered six F-117 stealth fighters to
Kuwait and six B-52 bombers to a British-controlled island in the
Indian Ocean, and authorized 30 additional aircraft if needed.
Iraq's Tariq Aziz met unexpectedly in Moscow with Yeltsin and
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who said they have
negotiated a plan to end the standoff peacefully. U.S. officials
were non-commital, however. 
