<HEADLINE> Pak Supreme Court Likely to Hear Petition Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of
Pakistan is likely to hear a petition filed against the amended
contempt law adopted by the Parliament Tuesday which is tending to
give protection to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in the ongoing case
of contempt against him in the apex court.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, the petition was filed today by
Syed Iftikhar Gilani challenging the vires of the amendment which,
in the petitioner's opinion, is mala fide and an attempt on
independence of judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Gilani is a former law minister belong to the Pakistan People's
Party, the biggest opposition party in the country.
</P>
<P>
The sources said an identical petition was also filed today by
Iqbal Haider, chairman of the Muslim Welfare Movement, and it is
likely to be clubbed with the petition of Gilani.
</P>
<P>
In his petition, Iqbal Haider stated that the amendment bill
was passed with mala fide intention and to provide safeguard to
the respondents in the contempt case being heard by the Supreme
Court these days, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The amended law, which provides for an intra-court appeal
before a "larger bench consisting of all the remaining available
judges of the court within the country", has been submitted to
President Farooq Leghari for signing.
</P>
<P>
The amended law came one day after Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
declined to tender an apology in the Supreme Court in the contempt
of court case against him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
