<HEADLINE> 102 People Apply to Run for HKSAR Deputies to  China's NPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 102 people have
obtained Registration Forms for Applicants for the Election of
Deputies of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) to
the Ninth National People's Congress of China.
</P>
<P>
By 5:00 p.m. today, 102 people had come to the registration
office at South Pacific Hotel to get their registration forms.
</P>
<P>
Among them are members of the Provisional Legislative Council,
people from commercial and industrial circles and the education
sector.
</P>
<P>
Nomination of candidates for HKSAR deputies to the Ninth NPC
began on November 13 and will last through November 28.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Method, the applicants must each
obtain Nomination Letters from at least 10 members of the
424-strong Election Conference.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Hong Kong to elect its own deputies
to the NPC as an independent constituency. The NPC is China's
supreme organ of state power.
</P>
<P>
The number of deputies to be elected in the HKSAR to the Ninth
NPC is 36, and the NPC deputies to be elected in the HKSAR must be
 Chinese citizens among HKSAR residents who are 18 years old or
above.
</P>
<P>
The election is selective with the number of candidates
exceeding the number to be elected by from one-fifth to one-half.
</P>
<P>
If the number of nominees does not exceed the number to be
elected by one-half, balloting can be conducted in one stroke.
</P>
<P>
If the number of nominees exceeds the number to be elected by
more than one-half, a preliminary round of balloting shall be
conducted by the Election Conference on all the nominees, to
determine the 54 official candidates on the merit of votes.
</P>
<P>
The election date is set on December 8, 1997. If a preliminary
round of balloting is called for, that will take place on December
 6, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
