<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Tightens Grip on Customs Duty Evading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has collected more
than 80 million Zimbabwe Dollars (six million U.S. Dollars) in
additional revenue in a major operation to swoop on traders
attempting to evade payment of duty, a local paper said today.
</P>
<P>
According to "The Herald" daily, the Depart of Customs and
Excise is also holding a further 277 cargo containers in the
operation started recently, in which at least half of all
containers are now being thoroughly examined by customs officers,
instead of just the one percent sample as was done in the past.
</P>
<P>
Director of Customs and Excise Ranga Munyaradzi said yesterday
that the 80 million Zimbabwe Dollars was collected in the first
two weeks of the operation while the 277 cargo containers were
netted in Harare alone.
</P>
<P>
The indefinite countrywide operation was started on october 13
and came hot on the heels of another successful operation by the
Income Tax Department.
</P>
<P>
More goods, which are still to have a direct contribution to
revenue, have been seized for mis-description, non-declaration,
undervaluation or just a bold attempt to smuggle, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said days of smuggling were now numbered and the department
was fast catching up with offenders. The sweeping exercise was
launched to curb rampant smuggling at points of entry.
</P>
<P>
The results of the exercise have by far surpassed
expectations. The Customs and Excise Department was looking at
raising 100 million Zimbabwe Dollars (70 million U.S. Dollars),
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
