<HEADLINE> Ericsson Sets Up Academy in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Sweden's Ericsson opened an
academy in Beijing on Tuesday to provide training for both
employees and customers as part of its strategy to increase
localization in China and technology transfers to China.
</P>
<P>
The Ericsson China Academy was built at a cost of nearly 10
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
It co-operates with the Fudan School of Management and the
Center for Nordic Studies at Shanghai's Fudan University, the
Norwegian School of Management, and Sweden's Lund University in a
program in management studies in information.
</P>
<P>
It leads to a Master of Management Studies degree granted by
the Norwegian School of Management. Ericsson has already set up
similar academies in Sweden, Malaysia, Australia and Ireland, but
the one in China is the first to grant the Master of Management
Studies degree.
</P>
<P>
By the turn of the century, China is expected to need about
300,000 MBA grads for management personnel, who will be especially
needed in state-owned enterprises. In the past five years, China
has only graduated about 1,200 MBAs each year. The country now has
more than 50 colleges and universities with MBA programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
