<HEADLINE> Land Auction Generates 64M US Dollars to HK Coffers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The first land auction after
 the stock market and currency turmoil saw two small lots sold for
 a satisfactory 497 million HK dollars (63.7 million U.S. dollars)
 here today.
</P>
<P>
The first lot, a 3,189-square-meter residential site at Chung
Hom Kok on the south side of Hong Kong Island, was sold for 221
million (28.3 million U.S. dollars), with bidding opened at 100
million HK dollars (12.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second one, a 693-square-meter site located at Hung Hom on
the southern tip of the Kowloon Peninsula, was sold for 276
million HK dollars (35.4 million U.S. dollars), with bidding
opened at 115 million HK dollars (14.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The two lots went to a single successful bidder, Yu Tai Hing
property company, after nearly 50 minutes' intense bidding among a
 couple of small and medium-sized property developers.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the property sector filled the auction
venue this afternoon, indicative of how the property market has
corrected after the recent financial turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The lots had been previously estimated to generate 150-230
million HK dollars (19.2-29.5 million U.S. dollars) and 185-265
million HK dollars (23.7-34.0 million U.S. dollars) respectively
to the coffers.
</P>
<P>
Lo Siu Tong, head of Yu Tai Hing, told reporters that the two
lots are a "good buy".
</P>
<P>
A smiling Lo said he is optimistic about the long-term prospect
 of the property market. "Tomorrow will be better," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first lot is intended for residential uses while the second
 for commercial-residential purposes.
</P>
<P>
The company has to complete a gross floor area of not less than
 1,400 square meters by June 30, 2001 for the first lot and not
less than 3,743 square meters by December 31, 2000 for the second.
</P>
<P>
Tony Chan, a chartered surveyor from Ricacorp Properties Group,
 commented that the small and medium-sized companies showed keen
interest in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the satisfactory results didn't necessarily
mean that the property market will recover immediately. Instead
they indicated the fine prospects two and three years away.
</P>
<P>
The property price has fallen 10 to 20 percent as a result of
the recent financial turmoil, with the luxury sector hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong shares reacted immediately to the auction results,
with the benchmark Hang Seng Index recouping over half of its
morning session loss to close the whole day at 10,154 points, 0.89
 percent lower compared with Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
