<HEADLINE> PUK Suffers Losses in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) suffered heavy losses in clashes with rival
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) in northern Iraq, the Turkish
Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The KDP launched a major offensive to drive the PUK out of the
village of Muhacir near the Iranian border and the two sides were
embroiled in fierce fightings, a KDP radio said.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here Tuesday by the KDP claimed the group
recaptured most of the territories lost to its rival.
</P>
<P>
The PUK reportedly had joined hands with Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in fighting the KDP since October 13,
taking over some of the territories controlled by the KDP,
allegedly supported by Ankara and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia said 23 PUK militants were killed during clashes with
the KDP in the regions of Sideka, Coman and Dolabanisan in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The two Kurdish factions have been fighting each other for the
control of northern Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War, when Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein was rendered ineffective by allied forces
to exert influence in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
