<HEADLINE> Southern African Leaders Support Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Southern African leaders
attending a trade and investment summit in Gaborone, Botswana
today repeated their support for President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
President Kabila is currently facing a United Nations probe
over alleged massacres of Rwandan refugees by his army, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions at the International Herald
Tribune-organized summit, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano rallied to Kabila's cause,
saying the former guerrilla leader needed the support of the
international community to stabilize the situation in the former
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy that there has been this campaign to unseat the
former president Mobutu Sese Seko. Several of our countries in
the region gave support to that campaign," Mugabe said referring
to the seven-month military push that forced Mobutu into exile in
Morocco where he died of cancer two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe accused the international community of seeking to
"demonize" Kabila without taking into cognizance the immense
challenges that he faces in stabilizing the situation in his
country.
</P>
<P>
He said while the probe into the alleged massacres of the
Rwandan refugees should go on, sight should not be lost of the
fact that Kabila needs support to stabilize the country and steer
it towards a democratic process.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano also stressed the urgency of stabilizing
the situation in the former Zaire, saying the new authorities
there might even make mistakes, but they should be helped to
eliminate those mistakes. 
</P>
