<HEADLINE> Khatami: Iran to Reform Economic System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has said that he has assigned a team to work out a
favorable economic system for the country, local media reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state television Tuesday on the
occasion of 100 days in office, Khatami said that the most
important task for his government was to improve the country's
economic structure in the fields of production, consumption and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
A long term plan to eradicate poverty must include measures
to bring about a proper production trend, Khatami said, adding
that the country has its disposal of both manpower and materials
needed to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the role of the private sector in the country's
economic life, the president said that the private sector should
be encouraged to invest its capital and at the same time taxes
should be levied on their activities.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the country was facing some serious economic
problems such as high inflation, Khatami said that the country
had gained outstanding achievements during the past years.
</P>
<P>
However, the English-language daily Iran News said today that
high prices of consumer goods, inflation, unemployment,
disinformation about high officials' power and authority in the
government have been a serious source of concern for ordinary
citizens in the country.
</P>
<P>
The paper said in an editorial that after Khatami's 100 days in
office, the people were expecting him to give at least a small
list of the steps his government has taken so far.
</P>
<P>
From the very first day of his election campaign, Khatami has
been talking about the rule of law, guarantees for freedom,
liberty and security, the daily said, but the people are getting
disappointed as more and more people are joining the ranks of
the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that people feel helpless in the face of their
diminishing purchasing power and gloomy future, adding that "it
is really a shame to see our educated youth become free-lane taxi
drivers in the city in order to meet their families' day-to-day
needs."
</P>
<P>
The people expect the president to inject a new life into
the nation's economy through his dynamic plans by taking strict
measures against profiteers and economic saboteurs, the paper
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
