<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Ministers to Meet on Energy, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chen Cailin)
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- African ministers
responsible for the development and utilization of mineral and
energy resources are to meet in Durban of South Africa later this
week to discuss development strategies in mineral and energy
industries, according to officials from the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA).
</P>
<P>
The immediate objective of the ministerial meeting, which is
organized by the ECA in collaboration with the South African
government, is to provide a forum for dialogue between
governments and energy and minerals development actors, while its
longer-term goal is to facilitate the adoption of sound
development policies and programs, provide a blueprint for future
action on a common denominator of interest between all secotrs,
the ECA officials said.
</P>
<P>
Before the ministerial meeting, there is a meeting of mining
and energy experts, private development operators and investors,
mineral-based products industrialists, minerals and energy
consumer associations, chambers of mines, research institutions,
and inter-governmental and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Africa is known of its rich mineral and energy resources. As
for proven mineral deposits in South Africa alone, gold accounts
for 39 percent of the world reserve, platinum 88 percent,
manganese 83 percent, while vanadium 45 percent, chromiu 72
percent, alumo-silicate 37 percent, vermiculite 40 percent, and
coal 11 percent. South Africa has been the largest producer and
exporter of minerals in the world.
</P>
<P>
Rich natural resources are bases for economic development in
Africa. However, statistics show that Africa's share of world
mineral production has consistently fallen since 1960 except of
bauxite, uranium and rutile. Mining production in Sub-Saharan
Africa accounts for only 8 percent of world mineral production,
so Africa now lags far behind latin america and asia in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa also lags far behind Latin America and Asia
in electricity production. Electricity supply is key to national
economic development and the raising of living standard. But, the
statistics show that some 77 percent of primary energy
consumption in Sub-Saharan Africa is of traditional and renewable
energy. Firewood accounts for 58.5 percent, charcoal for 18.1
percent, petroleum products for 15.5 percent, and coal,gas and
hydro-electricity account for 2.6 percent, 2.7 percent and 1.9
percent respectively. In 1993, the region produced only 49 kwh
per person of electricity, in comparision with 170 kwh for Asia
and 558 kwh for Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless,in the past few years, African countries have
attached great importance to the mineral and energy development.
The first minerals and energy conference organized by the ECA,
was held in Accra, Ghana in 1995. The confernece stressed that
African governments, the private sector, and non-governmental and
other actors were indispensable in the process of sustainable
development. It underlined the importance of economic reforms
which was under way in the region to facilitate the role of these
actors.
</P>
<P>
According to the ECA officials, mining now is dominated by the
private sector, with state-controlled operations
characteristically failing to keep up with the competition in an
increasingly globalized minerals industry. Policy reforms in a
number of African countries have focused on putting in place
enabling environments for foreign investment, seen as the best
option for maximising outputs in the under-exploited mining
sector. This policy shift are beginning to show positive results.
Africa's share in world private direct investment exceeded 12
percent in 1996, rising to 418 million U.S.Dollars in the year.
</P>
<P>
It is convinced that mineral and energy sectors in Africa will
be developed at the second ministerial meeting in Durban, the
African ministers will adopt a blue-print for future action which
will certainly promote the development of the minerals and
energy, thus raising the hope for the reduction of poverty in the
continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Processing Industry Grows in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The production of Angola's
processing industry increased by 16.1 percent from 1995 to 1996,
according to figures released today by the National Bureau of
Statistics of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Two years after the ceasefire was realized in war-torn Angola
in 1994, the production capacity of its processing industry
began to recover from a standstill caused by the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The growth from 1995 to 1996 was mainly attributed to the
increased production of drinks, especially beer, petroleum
products and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, oil refining, chemicals, machinery and
equipment have recorded fastest growths in the field of
processing industry.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that oil refining sector, chemicals
production and machinery and equipment sector have grown by 24.5
percent, 298.1 percent and 321 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
This has contributed to the whole processing industry's 13
percent of the total industrial production in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The mining is the biggest sector in Angola's industry,
accounting for 86.2 percent of the industrial production in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
