<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israeli Likud Mired in Deep Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli ruling Likud group
has been facing a crisis since last Wednesday's party convention
pushed through a proposal on abolishing primaries to give the
central committee the power to select candidates for Knesset
(parliament).
</P>
<P>
The struggle in the Likud over the primaries is essentially a
battle between the party's central committee stacked with Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's loyalists and its Knesset elite for
power and control of the party.
</P>
<P>
The party's 2,750 central committee members, who had charged
that the primaries cut the contact between the committee and the
party Knesset members, wanted to retain power over choice of the
party's candidates for the Knesset in its own hands and to take
part in significant policy decisions more actively.
</P>
<P>
While the Likud cabinet ministers fiercely oppose any change
in the party rules which would affect the primaries, since the
existing system confers considerable advantage upon the
incumbents in the choice of candidates for the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Some Likud members alleged that Prime Minister's office
Director-General Avidor Lieberman, widely considered Netanyahu's
right-hand man, had managed the last week's Likud convention via
remote control.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Science Minister Michael Eitan, one of Netanyahu's
most outspoken critics in recent days, accused the central
committee members of trying to boost their standing by acting on
Lieberman's behalf. He alleged there was "a large, planned
fraudulent network which started before the party institutions
and branches' elections."
</P>
<P>
With Netanyahu currently in London, his opponents have begun to
seek ways of replacing him.
</P>
<P>
Tel Aviv Mayor Ronni Milo, who resigned from parliament when
he assumed the mayor post, unveiled a plan Monday to steal the
Likud from beneath Netanyahu. He said that top Likud politicians
are cooperating in his plan to get 12 of the Likud's 22 Knesset
members to split the Likud Knesset faction.
</P>
<P>
The group of 12 would have the right to take the Likud name
and retain party financing. This would leave Netanyahu
effectively out of the party and unable to run for the prime
minister again on its ticket.
</P>
<P>
The plan aims to leave Netanyahu isolated without necessarily
forcing a change in the government, while assuring that the party,
in its new form, would field a new candidate in the next elections.
</P>
<P>
Milo, who has spared no effort in the last year-and-a-half to
undermine Netanyahu, said that "we are out to make sure that in
the next elections the Likud will no longer be under Netanyahu's
command, that he will not lead it and that the Likud will have a
fighting chance at winning power again."
</P>
<P>
In the campaign against Netanyahu, getting at least 12 Knesset
members to split the Likud faction is easier said than
done. However, finding enough Likud Knesset members to join a
Labor no-confidence motion against Netanyahu would appear a
simpler route to take.
</P>
<P>
During a secret meeting between Foreign Minister David Levy of
the ruling coalition and opposition Labor leader Ehud Barak last
Thursday, they reportedly discussed the option of bringing down
the government and holding early election over the government's
failure to move the peace process with the Palestinians forward.
</P>
<P>
Facing the crisis in the party, Netanyahu said in the
U.S. Monday that he would deal with the matter as soon as he
returned to Israel, noting that he would "fix what must be fixed
immediately" upon his return.
</P>
<P>
But as the primary issue has caused a deep rift between the
party's central committee members and its leadership, and
deepened crisis of mutual confidence between Netanyahu and some
ministers, no predictions about Netanyahu's ability to survive
can be taken seriously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
