<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's PLA Playing Role In Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The People's Liberation Army
(PLA) is playing an increasing role in China's environmental
protection endeavour, according to the 1997 China Environment
Forum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The PLA has put a large amount of funds into environmental
protection, and many of the Army's officers and enlisted personnel
are involved in environmental protection, Zhou Youliang, deputy
director of the PLA's General Logistics Department, told the forum.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years, the PLA has drafted many regulations on
environmental protection and its factories have made an effort to
save energy, reduce costs and deal with pollution, he said. They
have also increased research on environmental protection and
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the PLA to speak about its
environmental protection efforts at an international gathering,
and the PLA is important in both social construction and
environmental protection, Zhou noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese armed forces have also been involved in
afforestation, desert control, forest protection and wildlife
protection efforts. Millions of military personnel across the
country voluntarily plant trees each year. The Army's air wing has
scattered tree and grass seeds from the air over a
4.7-million-hectare area, and has had good results in waste water
and dust treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Army has established an environmental protection scientific
research center, an environment monitoring center, and an
environmental monitoring network, Zhou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
