<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Hands in Constituencies Delineation Order to PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China today handed in
an order declaring the delineation of constituencies for the first
Legislative Council election to be held in May next year to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC).
</P>
<P>
The Declaration of Constituencies (Legislative Council) Order
1997 was made by SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa in the
Executive Council under sections 18 and 19 of the Legislative
Council Ordinance, which came into operation on October 3.
</P>
<P>
The order was submitted to the PLC for negative vetting and it
will come into operation on January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the order, Hong Kong is divided into five
constituencies -- Hong Kong Island, Kowloon East, Kowloon West,
"New Territories" East and "New Territories" West.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Island constituency is allocated four seats, and
Kowloon East and Kowloon West get three seats each. Both "New
Territories" East and "New Territories" West get five seats.
</P>
<P>
Under the Legislative Council Ordinance, 20 members of the
60-seat Legislative Council will be elected from geographical
constituencies, 30 from functional constituencies and the other 10
will be elected by a 800-member Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
Michael Sun, secretary for constitutional affairs of the SAR,
today presented a report to the PLC for the explanation of the
order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
