<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,400-Year-Old Tombs Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- An ancient cemetery with
nearly 1,000 graves has been discovered in the city of Yiyang in
central China's Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
The graveyard, which dates back to the early and middle Warring
States (475-300 B.C.) period, according to a local archaeologist,
was uncovered at a construction site for a power plant.
</P>
<P>
It spreads across nine hills and contains coffin pits in a
dozen different styles, reflecting the social ranks of the people
they contain.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 pottery and bronze relics have been found in
the graves. Of the 300 bronze articles unearthed, 90 percent are
weapons. They indicate that those buried are some high-ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
Scholars believe that many people died as a result of the
constant wars of that period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Australian PM on China's Efforts for Environmental Issue (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Australia's former Prime
Minister Paul Keating spoke to the 1997 China Environment Forum
today about China's efforts to deal with its pressing
environmental problems, saying that the Chinese government has
given it high priority, and called on the rest of the world to
join the battle.
</P>
<P>
Keating told those present that the conference and China's
Agenda 21 strategy is evidence of its significant and sustained
efforts at cleaning up environmental problems and preventing new
ones.
</P>
<P>
China has been increasing its expenditures on environmental
protection, he said, and equally important, improving its
legislative, administrative, and policy framework for dealing with
the environment, but that it is essential that the rest of the
world understand the scale of China's environmental problem and
the challenge the Chinese authorities face.
</P>
<P>
"All the evidence suggests that the environmental
difficulties we face in the Asia Pacific over the next 25 years
will become more difficult to manage," he pointed out, noting that
if "we can help China resolve its problems, we are also helping
to resolve our own."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Australian PM on China's Efforts for Environmental Issue (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He added that the environmental problems faced by large
developing countries like China, or by industrialized countries
like the U.S. and Japan, or resource producers like Australia and
Canada, and small island states of the Pacific are very different,
but that in developing countries in Asia, problems tend to be
similar to China's.
</P>
<P>
This means poor and limited water supplies, polluted air, waste
disposal problems, chaotic urban planning, and land degradation,
and that many of these stem from rapid economic growth, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Asia's energy demands double every 12 years, with bad
consequences for air quality and global warming, and now, five of
the seven cities in the world with the worst air pollution are in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, around 500 million East Asians lived in
towns, he noted, but by 2020 this figure will have trebled to 1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
But, he pointed out, protection of the environment need not be
a constraint on economic growth, and it is the only way of
ensuring that such growth continues, and it is important to see
that the converse is true, that economic growth is essential to
solving environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
"For the countries of Asia, and for most of the developing
world, the option of limiting growth does not exist," he
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
