<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Should Keep Away From Tobacco: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior health official of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) today called for
joint efforts to protect children from becoming smokers.
</P>
<P>
Katherine Fok, Secretary for Health and Welfare, said here
today at a luncheon meeting: "It is everybody's business to save
children from the harm of tobacco."
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Hong Kong Council on Smoking and
Health (COSH) shows that many primary school students in Hong Kong
had the experience of smoking, and the situation was even more
serious in secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
She noted that many factors may induce children to smoke, such
as smoking in the home, movie characters who glamorize smoking,
peer pressure at school, and tobacco advertisements.
</P>
<P>
"It therefore becomes apparent that people in every sector of
the community -- parents, teachers, celebrities, private firms,
medical professionals -- need to collaborate in educating Hong
Kong's children, with the common goal of protecting them from
becoming smokers and being harmed by tobacco," said the official.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks at the meeting "Saving Children from the
Harm of Tobacco: Everybody's business", organized by the COSH,
which has launched a series of anti-smoking campaigns in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has introduced a law to prohibit the sale of tobacco
products to persons under the age of 18, but enforcement is no
easy task, according to Fok.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
