<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Milk Content Helps Baby Brain Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Medical researchers found
that Hong Kong women produce much more fatty acid Omega 3 in their
milk that is essential to brain growth of babies than Western
women do.
</P>
<P>
A medical study concluded that the total fat content of milk
from Hong Kong women contains 0.56 percent of Omega 3, compared
with 0.14 percent in Canadians and 0.54 percent in women of
Chongqing, a city in Southwest China, South China Morning Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Biochemistry Associate Professor Chen Zhenyu of the Hong Kong
Chinese University, who led the study, said the difference is
mainly in the diet.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong residents eat a lot of fish while Chongqing people
eat many eggs and both foods are rich in Omega 3, said Chen. The
study sampled the milk of 282 mothers from Canada and the two
Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Omega 3 can enhance brain development in children because it is
a key building block for nerve membranes in the brain, according
to experts. The substance can also reduce the chances of coronary
heart disease in adults.
</P>
<P>
But doctors noted that few Hong Kong babies benefit from the
high rate of Omega 3 in their mothers' milk because breast-feeding
is not popular here.
</P>
<P>
The breast-feeding rate is only 40 percent among Hong Kong
women, compared with more than 80 and 90 percent in Canada and
China's mainland respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
