<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Relations Entering New Phase of Development: Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, in a
report to officials here today, said that Sino-U.S. relations
entered a new phase of development after President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the United States, but improving and developing bilateral
ties is still a long and complicated process.
</P>
<P>
Qian, also foreign minister, spoke to a meeting of departments
directly under the CPC Central Committee and the State Council and
units of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) in the Great
Hall of the People, which was presided over by Ding Guangen, a
member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's state visit to the US was the first by a Chinese
president in 12 years and achieved its goal of increasing mutual
understanding, common ground, and co-operation for the future, Qi
said, and had immediate and far-reaching significance for the
world.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents discussed bilateral relations and major
international and regional issues and Jiang was able to talk
extensively with many people in the U.S. He made several important
speeches and held interviews with the American press.
</P>
<P>
The two president discussed the framework and orientation of
Sino-U.S. relations in the 21st century, and in spite of some
major differences, the two leaders found much in common, and
should have a long-term view of bilateral relations on the basis
of the three Sino-U.S. Joint Communiques to promote world peace
and development through increased co-operation and build a
constructive strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
These are normal state-to-state relations, and should be
characterized by equality, mutual respect, and non-exclusion of
others to maintain world peace and promote common development and
the progress of the mankind.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the Taiwan issue is the most important and most
sensitive issue in Sino-U.S. relations, and that the key to the
stable and healthy development of bilateral relations lies in
strictly abiding by the principles of the three Sino-U.S. Joint
Communiques.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reiterated its one-China policy, and President Clinton
and senior U.S. officials have explicitly stated time and again
that the U.S. government does not support "two Chinas" or "One
China, One Taiwan", nor does it support Taiwan independence or
Taiwan's re-entry into the UN. The U.S. will also handle arms sale
to Taiwan in line with the "August 17 Communique".
</P>
<P>
Much work remains to be done in Sino-U.S. relations, and the
Chinese side wish to increase consultations and co-operation with
the U.S. to properly deal with differences and China is resolved
to push ahead with bilateral relations, Qian concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
