<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Asian Cooperation Framework Replaces Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Senior financial officials from
the Asia-Pacific region today agreed to replace a proposed
independent regional fund with a new framework for enhanced
regional cooperation to promote financial stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of a two-day meeting here, the
officials said that they "agree on the need and desirability of a
framework for regional cooperation to enhance the prosperity for
financial stability" in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The framework, which recognizes the central role of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in the international monetary
system, has replaced a so-called "Asian Fund" proposed earlier by
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The new framework includes the following initiatives:
</P>
<P>
-- a mechanism for regional surveillance to complement global
surveillance by the IMF;
</P>
<P>
-- enhanced economic and technical cooperation particularly in
strengthening domestic financial systems and regulatory
capacities;
</P>
<P>
-- measures to strengthen the IMF's capacity to respond to
financial crises; and
</P>
<P>
-- a cooperative financing arrangement that would supplement
IMF resources.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the participants agreed on the need to
develop a cooperative financing arrangement for the region that
would supplement IMF and other international financial
institutions' resources.
</P>
<P>
"Under this arrangement participants could provide, in
consultation with the IMF and on a case by case basis,
supplemental financial resources for IMF-supported programs," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the participants also agreed on the
need to establish a new mechanism for regional surveillance.
</P>
<P>
"This mechanism would provide a basis for a more intensive and
high-level process of surveillance and dialogue among
participating finance ministers and central banks with support
from the IMF, the World Bank and the ADB (Asian Development
Bank)," it said.
</P>
<P>
"It will also help identify potential risks to growth and
financial stability and advise on appropriate policy responses to
reduce those risks," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that meetings for this purpose would be held twice a
year, with additional ones as warranted.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the officials stressed the importance of
economic and technical cooperation to strengthen banking and
financial systems.
</P>
<P>
They urged the IMF to constructively examine the establishment
of a new mechanism to provide short-term financing to augment an
exceptional standby or extended arrangement in the light of the
globalization of financial markets and the increased scale of
private capital flows.
</P>
<P>
At the joint IMF-World Bank annual meeting in Hong Kong in
September, Japan proposed the establishment of an "Asian Fund" to
help Southeast Asian countries to solve the on-going currency
crisis, but the United States gave a lukewarm response.
</P>
<P>
Other industrialized nations and the IMF have also resisted
Japan's idea of an independent "Asian Fund," as they fear that an
independent fund would undermine the IMF conditions attached to
its economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the Manila meeting is "a compromise" made by
Japan and the United States and the IMF, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The framework proposed at the Manila meeting would be discussed
at the informal ASEAN finance ministers' meeting in Kuala Lumpur
next month. If agreed by the ministers, such framework could be
presented to the ASEAN leaders' meeting in Kuala Lumpur on
December 15-16 for their approval.
</P>
<P>
Finance and central bank deputies from the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), the United States, Japan, China,
South Korea, Australia and other Asian and Pacific economies
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the IMF, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank were also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Japan agreed to host the next meeting of this forum early next
year to "carry forward the initiatives under the cooperation
framework."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria: 98,000 Children HIV Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- About 98,000 children in
Nigeria are estimated to be infected with the human
immuno-deficiency virus (HIV) which causes AIDS, according to the
United Nations Program on AIDS (UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
The agency also warned that the number will rise to 169,000 by
the year 2000 if the trend continues, the Midweek Concord
reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Kenneth Ofosu-Baku, UNAIDS country program
adviser, most of these children are made vulnerable to HIV
infection by exceptionally difficult conditions such as early
marriage and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS now estimates 8,500 new infections every day, out of
which 1,000 infections occur in children under the age of 15, he
said at a symposium here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by Nigeria's National AIDS Control Program
(NASCP) in 1996 shows that the average age of first sexual
exposure was 16 years for boys and 14.8 years for girls in the
country.
</P>
<P>
There were also instances where the age of first exposure was
eight years, said NASCP Coordinator N. Sani-Gwarzo.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, Nigeria has recorded more than
10,000 reported cases of AIDS since the inception of the disease
in 1982 and over four million Nigerians are infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
NASCP study shows that by the 1991-1992 period, there was only
about 1.5 percent infection among the population. But by the end
of last year, it had increased to about 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's population is estimated at about 100 million
currently.
</P>
<P>
It also reveals that the distribution of the infection among
the patients recorded 70 percent in the married couples, 22.7
percent in single persons, 9.1 percent in divorcees, eight
percent in students and below one percent among clergymen.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence rate through sexual intercourse is put at 56.74
percent in males and 43.26 percent in females, while 34 percent
is in prostitutes commonly known as commercial sex workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
