<HEADLINE> Indonesia Not to Reschedule Payment of Foreign Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia said it has no plan
of rescheduling the payment of its foreign debts which at present
amount to 117.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"A rescheduling is a bad signal to the public," Finance
Minister Mar'ie Muhammad told the Parliament today.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia's foreign debts reached 117.3 billion U.S. dollars
as of September this year as the government struggled to emerge
from its worst financial crisis in more than 30 years," Mar'ie
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign debts consist of 52.3 billion dollars in
government loans and 65 billion dollars in private loans, while
the debt service ratio is expected to reach 34.5 percent in the
fiscal year 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The September figure shows a 7.3 percent increase from the
total foreign debt last March which was 109.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie pointed out that the sharp depreciation of the rupiah
(the national currency) against the U.S. dollar would increase the
burden on the current state budget.
</P>
<P>
"every drop in value of the 100 rupiah against the dollar would
increase the government's debt service burden by 500 billion
rupiah (about 145 million U.S. dollars)," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the government would continue its
debt prepayment if financial condition allows. "Such a move is
very useful to revive the country's self-confidence."
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has seen the rupiah drop by about 40 percent in value
against the dollar since early July. The fall was in line with the
monetary crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the monetary crisis, the worst in more than 30
years, the government asked the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for help. Indonesia and the IMF reached an agreement in October on
a 23 billion U.S. dollar assistance and economic reform package
aimed to restore investors' confidence in the country's financial
system.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the debt-to-service ratio, the government agreed to
impose stricter requirements on the private sector's foreign loans
and step up efforts to increase exports.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that whatever the condition is, the
government will not make any bailout to private foreign debts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
