<HEADLINE> India's Textile Exports Register Sharp Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 19 (Xinhua) -- India's total textile
exports increased by over 17 percent during the first half of
fiscal 1997-98 (from April 1997 to March 1998) against shipments
in the same period last year, Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the country's textile
exports, including cotton, synthetic and woolen products, during
April-September this year were 94.80 billion rupees (about 2.60
billion U.S. dollars) against shipments worth 80.78 billion rupees
(about 2.21 billion dollars) in the corresponding period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Cotton textiles, including fabrics, yarn, sewing thread and
made-up, comprised 68 percent of the exports. Cotton textiles in
the first half of the current fiscal were valued at 65.10 billion
rupees (about 1.78 billion dollars) against 56.32 billion rupees
(about 1.54 billion dollars) last year. 
</P>
