<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Renewed weakness on some
Asian share markets and a plunging South Korean currency put a
damper on the Australian dollar today, pushing the local unit
down by almost half a U.S. cent.
</P>
<P>
However, the same factors gave the local bond market a boost,
with the day dominated by flight-to-quality buying.
</P>
<P>
The local unit settled at 69.35 U.S. cents, down from Tuesday's
close of 69.78.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Moore, St. George Bank manager of foreign exchange
trading, said a substantial fall on the Japanese share market and
a plunging South Korean currency gave the local forex market the
jitters.
</P>
<P>
"That's putting all the emphasis back on Asia and what is in
store for Australia," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean won was sharply lower today, despite a
dollar-selling intervention by the Bank of Korea right after the
won plunged to its limit low for the third consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the Nikkei 225 closed down 884.11 points at 15842.46,
pressured by sustained futures-led selling following the flip-flop
of statements by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on whether the
government would use public funds to assist troubled financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The weak Nikkei resulted in a stronger Australian dollar
against the Japanese yen at 87.98, from Tuesday's 87.66, but the
local unit was softer against the German mark at 1.1201 from
Tuesday's 1.2063. 
</P>
