<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Weaker as Asian Markets Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
dived more than one percent today on further falls in Asian
markets and poor commodity prices which dragged down resources
stock values.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 26 points to 2442.3 as the
Japanese and Hong Kong markets slipped further down.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications giant Telstra improved four cents to 2.57
Australian dollars on a volume of 119.3 million at a value of
212.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The emergence of Telstra cast a pall over resources giant BHP,
with brokers saying the company was no longer seen as a must-have
stock following Telstra's listing and the continued rise of
National Australia Bank.
</P>
<P>
Overnight falls in the world commodities markets also hurt BHP,
which fell 41.5 cents to close at 13.054 Australian dollars on
turnover of 14 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 20.1 points to 930.6.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 18.2 points to 1076.1 while the
all industrials closed 36.9 points lower at 4158.7.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Bank was the principal mover in industrial stocks, falling
33.8 cents to 9.94 Australian dollars after announcing an eight
percent drop in net profit to 706 million U.S. dollars for the
financial year of 1996-1997 which ended on June 30, 1997, below
most expectations.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank also suffered, falling 35 cents to 16.55
Australian dollars, with brokers attributing part of the fall to
concerns about the share buyback.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in banks, National Australia Bank fell 15 cents to
20.13 Australian dollars and Westpac shed 11 cents to 8.89
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 422.06 million shares at a
value of 904 million U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises
661 to 478.
</P>
