<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Plans 1998 Tuna, Swordfish Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
called, for the second year running, for annual quotas on Atlantic
tuna and swordfish and on Mediterranean tuna stocks.
</P>
<P>
The commission's proposal sets the European Union's total
allowable catch (TAC) for bluefin tuna at 4,492 tons for the
Atlantic Ocean with 85 percent going to Spain and 11,621 tons for
the Mediterranean Sea with 17 percent going to Spain, 42 percent
to France and 36 percent to Italy.
</P>
<P>
The quota plan was published in today's issue of European
Report, a bi-weekly journal specializing in European Union-related
matters.
</P>
<P>
For swordfish, the European Union's TAC is 5,462.5 tons with 83
percent going to Spain.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation union,
said that it wants the quota proposal for tuna and swordfish to be
part of a specific regulation distinct from the European Union's
general legislation on TACs and quotas.
</P>
<P>
Yet the European Union's Council of Ministers ignored the tuna
and swordfish quota proposals last year, arguing that it was not
an EU issue.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is not a contracting party of the
International Commission for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas,
the body in charge of coordinating action to manage fisheries in
the Atlantic and Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, however, has applied for membership and is
expected to be admitted shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
