<HEADLINE> Kampala to Have Hi-Tech Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A group of South Africa-based
Ugandan doctors planned to establisah a hi-tech hospital in
Kampala, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dominic Drabile, leader of the group, told Eriya Kategaya, the
first deputy prime minister, that the investment of 12.2 million
of U.S. dollars will be provided by bank loans and collected by
shares.
</P>
<P>
Donald Amoko, one of the doctors, told the paper that the
hospital will perform hi-tech operations except heart and liver
transplants. Complicated cases will be dealt by telemedicine. The
specialists in South Africa will assist local medical staff
through monitor screens.
</P>
<P>
The three storied hospital with 128 beds will take more than
one year weeks for its construction. It will be operating in
1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The hospital will allocate every 30 beds for medical, surgical
and maternity departments, 12 beds for pediatrics, 10 for
gaenecology and two for neonatal, four for adult intensive units
and ten for day clinic for simple surgery.
</P>
<P>
The hospital will also have 21 consulting rooms.
</P>
<P>
The hospital will also train local medical staff to operate
sophisticated equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
