<HEADLINE> Japan, Philippines Agree on Need For Financial Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and Visiting Philippine President Fidel Ramos agreed
today to promote the establishment of a financial support
mechanism to address the recent currency crisis in Southeast Asia,
Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting between Hashimoto
and Ramos at the Japanese prime minister's official residence.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who arrived here Tuesday for a two-day visit, told
Hashimoto that he expects a positive outcome from the ongoing
meeting of senior finance officials in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Deputies of finance ministers and central bankers from Japan,
the United States and the nine-member Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) as well as officials from international
monetary bodies are discussing a proposed Asian monetary facility
to ensure the crisis will not recur.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said, "It is important that all the related countries
will cooperate and coordinate to tackle the currency crisis in Asia."
</P>
<P>
Japan is Ramos's first leg of a 15-day three-nation tour which
will later take him to the United States before he attends the
November 24-25 informal summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum in Vancouver, Canada. 
</P>
