<HEADLINE> Board Meeting of Partners in Population and Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The third annual board meeting
of the Partners in Population and Development ended here today in
Dhaka, further strengthening South-South collaboration in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
Applications for partnership by China and Pakistan were
approved by the board at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Attending the three-day meeting were over 150 people including
several ministers, top officials in charge of population policy
and specialists from the original 10-partners and two new
partners, and representatives of international agencies and NGOs,
as well as observers from Iran, Tanzania and India.
</P>
<P>
The partners' initiative was launched at the 1994 International
Conference on Population and Development (ICPD) in Cairo by
Bangladesh, Colombia, Egypt, Indonesia, Kenya, Mexico, Morocco,
Thailand, Tunisia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The 12-partner countries are internationally recognized as
having developed effective population policies, programs and
services, and as being strongly committed to the implementation of
the ICPD program of action.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, participants reviewed the implementation of
improved reproductive health and family planning programs through
expanded South-South collaboration, and exchanged experiences in
this field.
</P>
<P>
They also reviewed progress made so far by the South-South
initiative, and discussed the Dhaka-based secretariat's
operational plan for 1997-1999.
</P>
<P>
They called on all developing countries to step up their
efforts in implementing the 20-year program of action which was
endorsed by 180 countries in Cairo in 1994 through South-South
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
The first and second annual meetings were held in Harare and
Mexico City in 1995 and 1996 respectively. The just
concluded-meeting decided that the next annual meeting will be
held in Cairo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
