<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Taxes Continue to Rise in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Employment taxes are on the
rise in the European Union (EU), totaling 42.1 percent of wages in
1995 as against 28.7 percent in 1970, according to today's issue
of European Report.
</P>
<P>
The bi-weekly journal quoted a Eurostat survey as saying that
taxes on employed labor are highest in Sweden and Finland and
lowest in Britain and Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Between 1985-1995, the largest increases of taxes on employed
labor were seen in Germany, from 39.5 percent to 44.1 percent, in
Spain, from 32.3 percent to 38 percent, in Italy, from 36.6
percent to 44 percent, in Portugal, from 21.4 percent to 36.7
percent, and in Finland, from 42.9 percent to 53.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Decreases were seen during the same period in Luxembourg, from
32.5 percent to 29.6 percent, in the Netherlands, from 50.9
percent to 48.8 percent, and in Ireland, from 30.2 percent to 30.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat survey found that taxes on employed labor as a
percentage of employee wages have risen sharply over the past 25
years while total tax receipts on employed labor increased from
43.2 percent to 51.4 percent between 1970-1995 in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The share of taxes on employed labor in gross domestic product
also rose from 14.5 percent to 21.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
union, submitted to the Council of Ministers last month its set of
guidelines for promoting employment to stress the dire need to
reform the existing systems of taxation on employed labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
