<HEADLINE> 84 Arrested After Zambia Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 84 people have been
detained in connection with the October 28 foiled coup in Zambia,
according to Government Gazette.
</P>
<P>
Of these arrested, 31 suspects have been detained at Lusaka
Central Prison, 42 at Mukobeko Maximum prison in Kabwe in central
Zambia and the rest are at Kamfinsa Prison in Kitwe, in the north
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrested are Dean Mung'omba, the president of the
opposition Zambia Democratic Congress and the coup leader captain
Jackson Chiti and captain Steven "Solo" Lungu.
</P>
<P>
Some of the officers and soldiers were picked up on the day of
the attempted coup on the spot and scores of others were arrested
from various military cantonments after the coup.
</P>
<P>
In early morning of October 28 Lungu and about 30 others
seized state radio in the Mass Media Complex in Lusaka and
announced that they had taken over state power.
</P>
<P>
The coup was foiled a few hours later by the forces loyal to
the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
