<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Officials Agree on Cooperation Framework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Asian and Pacific financial
officials ended their two-day meeting here today with an agreement
on the need of a new framework for regional cooperation, instead
of an independent "Asia Fund" proposed earlier to promote
financial stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of the meeting, the delegates
said that they "agree on the need and desirability of a framework
for regional cooperation to enhance the prosperity for financial
stability" in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The framework recognizes the central role of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in the international monetary system, they
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the framework, a cooperative financing arrangement
would supplement IMF and other international financial
institutions' resources.
</P>
<P>
"Under this arrangement participants could provide, in
consultation with the IMF and on a case-by-case basis,
supplemental financial resources for IMF-supported programs," the
participants said.
</P>
<P>
The participants also agreed on the need to establish a new
mechanism for regional surveillance.
</P>
<P>
At the joint IMF-World Bank annual meeting in Hong Kong in
September, Japan proposed the establishment of an "Asian Fund" to
help Southeast Asian countries to solve the on-going currency
crisis, but the United States gave a lukewarm response.
</P>
<P>
Other industrialized nations and the IMF have also resisted
Japan's idea of an independent "Asian Fund," as they fear that an
independent fund would undermine IMF conditions attached to its
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
Bowing to pressure from the United States and the IMF, Japan
scaled back its proposal.
</P>
<P>
The framework proposed at the Manila meeting would be discussed
at the informal ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
finance ministers' meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, next month.
If agreed by the ministers, such a framework could be presented to
the ASEAN Leaders' meeting in Kuala Lumpur on December 15-16 for
their approval.
</P>
<P>
Finance and central bank deputies from ASEAN, the United
States, Japan, China, South Korea, Australia and other Asian and
Pacific economies attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the IMF, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank were also present at the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: South Korean Government Economy Team Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam Wednesday dismissed two top economic officials -- Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance and Economy Minister Kang Kyong-shik
and Senior Presidential Secretary for Economic Affairs Kim In-ho,
just three months before the end of his five-year presidential
term.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle came after a financial-reform bill, proposed by
the government led by Deputy Prime Minister Kang, failed to be
passed at the National Assembly session Tuesday because of the
parties' different attitudes on it.
</P>
<P>
The session decided to postpone the reform package, which is
considered as Kang's last effort to stablize the nation's shaky
financial market.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Kang also felt strong pressure to step down
because of the recent economic turmoil in the country. Critics
blame it was stemmed from the government's unrealistic policies.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office in early March, the prime minister has
devoted a lot to reform the country's defective economic systems,
including the primitive financial sector.
</P>
<P>
But in this process, he has been constantly criticized for
lacking a sense of reality and failing to put financing touches on
what was started recklessly.
</P>
<P>
Critics blame most recent economic setbacks on Kang's
incompetence -- failure to produce timely policies -- as was seen
in the case of the Kia Group, to which most experts attributed the
current financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
As the near-collapse of the Kia Group was throwing the economy
into turmoil by increasing uncertainty in the financial markets,
Kang was criticized to have folded his arms, reiterating that the
government would not meddle in private business.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the bank's bad-debt problems went from bad to
worse, bringing the country's overseas funding to a virtual halt.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is now facing a serious shortage of foreign
currency with the local currency won racing to renew its record
lows against the dollar day after day and stock prices plunging.
</P>
<P>
South Korean banks as well as merchant banks, suffering from
their declining credit ratings originated from the huge
non-performing loans to businesses, found it impossible to borrow
from abroad and have difficulties in lending foreign currency to
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Kang had announced a series of measures to stablize the
financial markets as well as promote the inflow of foreign
exchange, but failed to achieve any results.
</P>
<P>
There was even rumors spread recently that South Korea is
seeking an International Monetary Fund (IMF) rescue fund which the
Ministry of Finance and Economy firmly denied.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts say Kang seems inappropriate for the post of top
economic policy maker of an administration whose days are numbered.
</P>
<P>
"If he had been the top policy maker at the start of an
administration, he would have been remembered as a successful
deputy prime minister by tackling the country's structural
problems," an analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the reshuffle conducted three months before the
end of term indicated president Kim's determination to overcome
the economic difficulties facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The financial circles welcomed Lim Chang-yuel, Trade, Industry
and Energy Minister and also a financial expert with decades-long
experience at the ministry to succeed as the top economic
policy-maker and hopes the new administration will take realistic
steps to work out the difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discounts for Air Travelers within China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Both overseas and domestic
travelers who take flights within China, including domestic
sections of international flights, will have a chance at price
discounts ranging from 5 to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Individual travelers can get reductions from 5 to 20 percent,
while 40 percent discounts will be available for teachers and
students during summer and winter holidays, the elderly and group
travelers.
</P>
<P>
Airlines will have the final say on the amount of discounts
based on market conditions, air routes and other factors.
</P>
<P>
This preferential treatment will cover early-morning and night
flights, maiden flights, return flights, and frequent flyers'
programs, said Hai Liancheng, director of the Financial Affairs
Department of the Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
He said there are still some restrictions for the preferential
policies. Men must be 60 or older and women must be 55 to
qualify for the elderly fare. Teachers and students, soldiers and
the disabled must provide corroborating documentations.
</P>
<P>
Preferential tickets cannot be returned and their holders are
not allowed to transfer to another place, and seats cannot be
booked in advance, Hai said.
</P>
<P>
Airlines will make public the different kinds of discount
tickets, the restrictions, and appropriate telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
Hai said the effort is to satisfy various consumer demands and
provide more choices for travelers, taking full advantage of the
potential of civil aviation and making air travel more competitive
in the transport market.
</P>
<P>
A number of airlines have already implemented the discount
system, but their offerings are temporary. The measure has been
adopted on international flights managed by CAAC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
