<HEADLINE> Russia Rejects Bonn's Spying Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador Sergie Krylov
has rejected German media reports that as many as 165 spies were
operating out of the Russian embassy and consulates in Germany,
describing such an idea as "absurd," said reports published today.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is there are only 50 Russian diplomats here at the
Bonn embassy. That means that members of their families -- their
wives and children -- and even the cleaning ladies would have to
work as spies," Krylov told the daily newspaper Bild.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of weekly news magazine Der Spiegal claimed
that Russia's espionage activities had increased over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, German security authorities identified 165
Russian spies in Germany, 60 in Bonn and 56 in Berlin, it reported.
</P>
<P>
It said Bonn was pressing for Moscow to withdraw its spies no
later than moving its diplomatic bodies to capital Berlin.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl was to discuss the issue with
Russian leadership when he visited the country in the end of
November, it added. 
</P>
