<HEADLINE> East China Improving Wild Animal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Wild Animal Protection
Association in east China's Jiangsu Province is making progress in
helping establishing a nature preserve on the coast to protect rare
birds.
</P>
<P>
After a decade of work, the number of red-headed cranes in the
preserve has grown to 1,020, making it one of the largest habitats
for the bird. In the Dafeng Nature Preserve, the number of David's
deer has increased from 39 to 302.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is also emphasizing law enforcement
to protect wild animals.
</P>
<P>
In Suzhou, three restaurants were penalized for selling
pangolins, and in Wuxi, suspected illegal traders of wild animals
were arrested. 
