<HEADLINE> Stocks Tumble in Tokyo on Financial System Jitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices plummeted
today to the 15,000 yen level again on renewed concern over the
Japanese financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, plunged 884.11 points, the year's
largest point fall, or 5.29 percent from Tuesday's close, to
15,842.46.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues
on the First Section, declined 58.43 points or 4.56 percent to
1,221.60.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 600 million
shares, down from Tuesday's 649.54 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Yamichi Securities was today's most actively trade issue.
</P>
<P>
A comment by Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto late
Tuesday that he had said nothing to suggest that the government
may use public funds to aid the troubled financial system spurred
selling.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar moved higher to
the 127 yen level for the first time since early May.
</P>
<P>
After hitting a high of 127.08 yen, the dollar changed hands at
126.91-93 yen at 5 p.m., up from 126.11-14 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo
and from 126.10-20 yen late Tuesday in New York. 
</P>
