<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lure of Gold Attracts Prospectors to Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The lure of gold has attracted
both overseas firms and domestic enterprises to the Qianxinan
Bouyei-Miao Autonomous Prefecture in southwest China's Guizhou
Province.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies and domestic enterprises both are vying for
a chance to prospect in the region, which reportedly has proven
gold reserves of 136 tons.
</P>
<P>
During the last few years, government surveyors have found four
big mines, including Lannigou Gold Mine.
</P>
<P>
Lannigou Gold Mine, which is reported to have verified gold
reserves of 60.5 tons, has been listed by the state as a major
site for overseas cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A dozen overseas delegations from the United States, Canada and
other countries have made investigation tours of Lannigou.
</P>
<P>
At present, the state and concerned enterprises have been
operating more than 100 mines, which are required to sell
their gold to the government at state-set prices.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture produced 2,200 kilograms of gold last year, said
Huang Kangsheng, head of the prefecture government.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that mining in the prefecture has bright
prospects as gold ores there are comparatively concentrated and
convenient for exploitation.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped more overseas investors would be attracted to
the region.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure in the region is also improving, he said, citing
examples of the Nanning-Kunming Railway that will begin service
early next month and construction of a hydropower station with an
installed capacity of 2.52 million kilowatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Build Less Golf Courses Due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- All applications for conversion
of land into golf courses were held in abeyance due to the El Nino
abnormal weather phenomenon, a government official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Agrarian Reform Undersecretary Artemio Adasa said that in light
of El Nino, all golf courses are now banned in environmentally
critical areas such as wetland, national parks, prime agricultural
land and places with water shortage.
</P>
<P>
"No golf zones would be issued on said areas and at the same
time should not encroach on areas already covered by the country's
comprehensive agrarian reform program," Adasa quoted a resolution
issued by the Golf Course Construction Committee as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that a total of 410 hectares of land recently applied
for conversion in two provinces will be affected by the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution identified degraded places such as landfill
sites and mines areas as the most suitable areas for developers to
build golf courses, he said.
</P>
<P>
To battle the drought brought about by El Nino, the Philippine
government is taking various measures to conserve and recycle
water.
</P>
</TEXT>
