<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Calls for Social Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz has urged to set up a dialogue and cooperation mechanism to
solve social problems, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not do that, we are bound to lag behind the
contemporary world," Yilmaz warned in an article published in the
latest issue of a publication of Turkey's Metal Industrialists
Union, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
He said that modern industry not only offers opportunities to
the society, but also brings problems of unemployment, poverty as
well as violence.
</P>
<P>
All these problems will not be settled without a dialogue and
understanding mechanism among all sectors of the society, he added.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz suggested carrying out political reforms, reorganizing
political structures of Turkey in a bid to promote participation
of all citizens.
</P>
<P>
Citing the Economic and Social Council as an example, he called
for establishing similar organizations which can create the
atmosphere of social consensus, cooperation and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
These groups will contribute to the protection and extension
of individual rights and freedom in Turkey, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been criticized by its Western allies for the
human rights record, which is a major obstacle to its bid for
European Union membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
