<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Writers Win Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Ethnic minority writers and
translators were given a national prize here today for their
literary work.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Lhoba, Jino, and Tatar ethnic groups won the
National Ethnic Minorities Literary Creation Award, which is the
major prize for ethnic minority writers, for the first time. As a
result, all of China's 56 ethnic groups are represented with prize
winners.
</P>
<P>
This was the fifth time that the prize, which was established
in 1981, has been awarded. This year's 63 winners are from 24
ethnic groups and include 11 females, and have 19 books, or 31
percent of the prize-winning works, written in ethnic languages
that include Tibetan, Uygur, and Mongolian.
</P>
<P>
In the 16 years since the prize was established it has been
awarded to 500 writers. Critics say that it shows how literary
works are flourishing in ethnic minority areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
