<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advance Party to Prepare For Peace Monitoring in PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- An advance party of
Australian and New Zealand defense personnel will meet in Papua
New Guinea (PNG) tomorrow, before heading to PNG's rebel island of
Bougainville to pave the way for a truce monitoring group, the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Defense Force (NZDF) Spokeswoman Major Fiona
Cassidy said 17 or 18 unarmed members of the NZDF would leave New
Zealand early tomorrow morning for Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of peace monitors in PNG will coincide with the
start of fresh peace talks in Cairns, North Queensland of
Australia, between officials from all parties of the Bougainville
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer earlier announced
14 members of the Australian Defense Force would be in
Bougainville by Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It's one group, they're going to be marrying up," Major
Cassidy told AAP.
</P>
<P>
"The whole contingent is getting together in (Port) Moresby,
and sorting out exactly who's doing what and where they're going
and then they'll go on to Bougainville."
</P>
<P>
After joining together in PNG, Major Cassidy said the advance
party would then head to Bougainville to begin scouting the four
locations for the Truce Monitoring Group which would begin
arriving later this month.
</P>
<P>
"We're waiting for a date which is anywhere between the 26th
and 27th for the main advance party to head for Bougainville,"
Major Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Truce Monitoring Group members would not act as
peacekeepers, and would only observe any possible breaches of the
ceasefire between the secessionist Bougainville Revolutionary Army
and the PNG defense force.
</P>
<P>
Major Cassidy said New Zealand would contribute 136 personnel
to the group, in addition to the frigate of Canterbury, which
leaves for Bougainville tomorrow, tanker Endeavor and air support.
</P>
<P>
She said Australia would be contributing 90 to 92 people to the
group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
