<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases in China Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The number of cases of
HIV/AIDS reported in China had risen to 8,277 by the end of
September, the Ministry of Health disclosed here today.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 168 of the patients had AIDS and 77.5 percent were
drug users. From January to September, 2,237 new HIV positive
cases have been found, according to Wang Zhao, director of the
Ministry of Health's Disease Control Department, who spoke here
today at an AIDS conference sponsored by the Health Ministry and
UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
Based on 1996 figures, it is estimated that China may already
have 150,000 to 200,000 people infected. AIDS in China has entered
a third stage since 1994. It started among the transient
population and paid blood donors in central parts of China, and
spread among drug users in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
and Sichuan Province last year.
</P>
<P>
The HIV virus began to spread in the 1980s, and today 30
million people in the world have been infected with the deadly
disease, 90 percent of them in developing countries, 40 percent,
women, and ten percent, children. The disease was first discovered
in China in 1985, and the number of cases of HIV/AIDS caused by
sexual contacts continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS and Children" will be the theme of the '97 World AIDS Day
on December 1, which will focus on protecting children from
HIV/AIDS, said Emile Fox, an official with the United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
China will hold a campaign on HIV/AIDS prevention in Beijing,
Hong Kong, and areas along the Beijing-Kowloon Railway in December
for World AIDS Day, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
