<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Drafts New Campaign Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Presidential candidate Raila
Odinga has confirmed that several Kenyan opposition leaders are
consulting to come up with a strategy to ensure victory in the
multi-party general elections set for December 29.
</P>
<P>
The consultations include a possibility of agreeing on a
single opposition presidential candidate to take on President
Daniel arap Moi and reducing the number of contestants for the
presidency, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need to divide the votes of the opposition,"
Odinga, also the chairman of the National Development Party, was
quoted by today's Daily Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The (ruling party) KANU government thinks they can rig them
by dividing opposition votes. But we think that we can
consolidate our votes and come out the winners," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He added a technical team comprising senior members of various
opposition parties are also discussing issues such as how the
parties would share certain portfolios after the elections.
</P>
<P>
However, he refused to reveal which opposition parties have
been involved in the consultation. 
</P>
