<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banker Optimistic About S. African Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa could look
forward to a better economic performance in 1998 after a
successful consolidation period in 1997, Reserve Bank Governor
Chris Stals said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen newspaper quoted Stals as telling an investment
conference that a host of factors supported his view that the
consolidation process in the country's business cycle had been
completed.
</P>
<P>
These included improved equilibrium between real total
domestic production and real total demand, a surplus on the
overall balance of payments, a slowdown in money supply and bank
credit extension growth, higher gold and foreign exchange
reserves, falling inflation and a stable nominal effective
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"Not everything is, however, favorable for an expected
economic recovery in South Africa next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the possible adverse effects of current turbulence in
Asian markets, the lower gold price and the impact of the El Nino
weather phenomenon would have to be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
"On balance, South Africa can with justification look forward
to a better economic performance in 1998 after the successful
consolidation period of 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stals reiterated that the central bank would continue
gradually easing its monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to be guided by financial aggregates," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after peaking at 23.6 percent in the first
quarter of this year, rate of growth in total bank credit
extension had declined to 6.2 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
