<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Preparations for the space shuttle Columbia's
Wednesday blastoff finished Tuesday, said officials with the
United States' National Aeronautics and Space Administration
(NASA).
</P>
<P>
A multinational crew, on the 16 day scientific research
mission, will board the space shuttle to be launched at 2:46
p.m. U.S. eastern standard time (19.46 GMT) from the Kennedy Space
Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 30 school children died and more than 60
injured when an overcrowded school bus plunged into the Yamuna
River in north New Delhi early Tuesday, the local press said
today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports had put the toll at 20.
</P>
<P>
The disaster occurred when the bus, which was reportedly
speeding, skidded on a mound of sand lying in one lane of a bridge
over the river and crashed into the railings of the bridge before
plunging into the Yamuna.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam Wednesday
dismissed Deputy Prime Minister and Finance and Economy Minister
Kang Kyong-shik and Senior Presidential Secretary for Economic
Affairs Kim In-ho.
</P>
<P>
Trade, Industry and Energy Minister Lim Chang-yuel replaced
Kang as Deputy Prime Minister for Finance and Economy.
</P>
<P>
Kim Yong-sup, head of the Customs Administration, was named the
new Senior Presidential Secretary for Economic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Sri Lankan security forces in the north and east
have been put on alert following reports that Tamil rebels are
preparing to celebrate their "Great Heroes Week" from November 20
to 27, security sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Usually the rebels would step up violence during the period in
remembrance of their cadres who have lost their lives in the
14-year-long ethnic war, which the rebels have been fighting in a
bid to create a state of their own in the north and east of the
country. 
</P>
