<HEADLINE> Hingis Advances on McCarthy's Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Dutch big-serving Brenda
Schultz-McCarthy failed to block top seed Martina Hingis for her
13th title this year, pulling out for toe injury in the second set
of a first-round match in the Chase Championships here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who has a record 75-4 running in 1997, ousted McCarthy
7-6 (7-3), 5-2 to advance into the quarter-finals, setting up a
meeting with French Mary Pierce who beat Sabine Appelmans of
Belgium on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Schultz-McCarthy, who blasted the hardest serves in women's
tennis, stormed eight aces and broke once in the first set, making
a stunning challenge to the world No. 1 player, before the Swiss
teenager came back from 2-1 in the tiebreaker and struggled
through the opening set.
</P>
<P>
But the Dutch tore off the nail on her right toe while she
casted herself on a volley in the first game of second set. After
that, she could not keep up with Hingis' pace and retired at 5-2.
</P>
<P>
"The nail completely went off the toe," said
Schultz-McCarthy. "I can hardly walk. I guess it's just bad
luck. I played seven weeks in a row, so I guess my body is
exhausted."
</P>
<P>
Hingis has won 12 tournaments this year, including the
Wimbledon, Australian and U.S. Open, with the French Open going to
Iva Majoli of Croatia, a step away to sweep the Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
In Tuesday's earlier match, Majoli took a revenge by beating
Anke Huber of Germany 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (7-2) and ran their
head-to-head contest to 3-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
