<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang: Sino-U.S. Cooperation Encouraging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today that the cooperation between China and the United
States on economic, trade, science and technology issues has a
promising future.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with John Gibbons, assistant to U.S. president
Bill Clinton for science and technology policy, Jiang said the
level of such cooperation is still low in comparison to both
countries' needs for economic growth, and that the potential of
such cooperation is yet to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are faced with an "unprecedented opportunity"
to further economic, trade, scientific and technological
cooperation, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes both sides will continue efforts to promote
such cooperation, thus benefiting the people of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the ever-developing science and technology fields
are producing a profound impact on the pattern of world politics
and economy.
</P>
<P>
He said China, which is opening wider to the outside world and
striving for modernization, needs to learn from all the
outstanding scientific results from all over the world, including
the American people.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said his recent state visit to the United States has
turned out to be a successful one.
</P>
<P>
He and President Clinton reached a consensus on the framework
of developing Sino-U.S. relations oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
This is not only in the fundamental interests of the Chinese
and American people, but also will benefit world peace and
development, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Gibbons said the United States holds that Jiang's visit not
only added fuel to the development of Sino-U.S. relations but also
opened up broad prospects for scientific and technological
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the consensus reached by Clinton and Jiang
on expanding Sino-U.S. cooperation in science and technology,
Gibbons said the eighth China-U.S. Joint Committee meeting on
science and technology cooperation has produced progress in many
areas.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side is to work with the Chinese to promote
scientific and technological cooperation between the two
countries, Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
Gibbons and his party are here at the commission meeting at the
invitation of Song Jian, China's State Councillor and Minister in
charge of State Science and Technology Commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
