<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Relics Found at 3,000-year-old Site in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Boneware and pottery dating
back 3,000 years, along with carved hollow bricks, bronze, and
porcelain from later dynasties, have been found in the capital of
central China's Henan province.
</P>
<P>
The relics were unearthed at the site of a city from the Shang
Dynasty (16th-11th Century BC) where a highway is going to be
built. In checking the site before construction, local
archaeologists found 41 tombs from the Han (206 BC-220 AD), Tang
(618-907), and Song (960-1279) dynasties, in addition to bone
combs, hairpins, arrowheads, oracle bones, and pottery containers
from the Shang.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists have excavated nine of the tombs, including
a Han tomb with hollow bricks carved with designs of processions,
buildings, trees, and birds, and a Tang tomb with incense burner,
and celadon and white or yellow-glaze porcelain.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the find will contribute to the study of
ancient burial customs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
