<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Shoulder Tasks of Environmental Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The late Chinese leader Mao
Zedong's saying "women holding up half the sky" highlights the
important role Chinese women play in politics, the economy and
society, as well as in the increasingly pressing tasks of
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing '97 China Environment Forum, Huang Qizao,
vice-president of the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF), said
that since 1990 more than 120 million Chinese women have
participated in afforestation every year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women also play an important role in environmental
research, pollution control, population control, protection of
nature and environmental education, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
During the past seven years, the forum was told, Chinese women
have built more than 100,000 greenbelts that include
shelter-forests, orchards, mulberry fields and nurseries of young
plants.
</P>
<P>
According the Ministry of Forestry, the survival rate of trees
planted by women has reached 85 percent. In addition, the ministry
allocated 800,000 yuan (97,000 U.S. dollars) annually to support
the building of 25 model greenbelts by ACWF in 18 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the central
government.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Province, one of the important forest areas in eastern
China, has organized more than 3,000 teams of women who have
planted 63,000 hectares of trees during the last six years.
</P>
<P>
Women in central China's Hunan Province, one of the country's
grain production centers, make use of their courtyards to plant
fruit trees, tea, and herbs to bring in more income for their
families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
