<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Shoulder Tasks of Environmental Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Niu Yuqin, a woman in northwestern China's Shaanxi Province,
moved her home to the edge of the desert. Over the past decade,
she and her family have planted more than 930 hectares of trees,
winning praise from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
At the eighth government-to-government negotiation meeting of
the U.N. International Convention on Combating Desertification in
1996, 44-year-old Wang Guoxiang, a woman from northern China's
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, was invited for her contribution
to desert control and afforestation.
</P>
<P>
"My hometown is located in the dunes," Wang said. "The severe
environment had made our life poor. Many villagers had moved away,
and men worked elsewhere to support the family."
</P>
<P>
Wang said the women and children who were left behind had no
other way but to plant trees and fight back the sand. After a
decade, they have built orchards on the desert, growing grapes and
Chinese wolfberries.
</P>
<P>
"Many villagers built new houses with their increased income,
and those who had moved away returned to their hometown," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, ACWF and the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection initiated an environmental education campaign among
Chinese women, giving full play to women's special role in
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The organizer of the activities said the increase of women's
environmental awareness will help form proper ecological habits in
their children, and promote awareness throughout the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
