<HEADLINE> Iran to Launch 12 Petrochemical Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The National Iranian
Petrochemical Company (NIPC) has announced to launch 12
petrochemical projects in the coming four years, local newspaper
Iran Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Oil Minister and NIPC Managing Director
Mohammad Reza Nematzadeh made the announcement Tuesday in an
interview with the daily.
</P>
<P>
Nematzadeh said that the projects with an estimated cost of 2.5
billion U.S. dollars are designed to yield an annual production of
6.5 million tonnes of plastics, fertilizers and detergents, which
are expected to make 4 billion dollars for Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has produced a total of 6.4 million tonnes of
petrochemicals in the first seven months of this Iranian year
starting from March 21, showing a 15 percent increase compared
to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Nematzadeh said that during the period Iran has exported 2
million tonnes of various kinds of petrochemicals and earned 363
million dollars, registering a 29 percent rise compared to the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, India, China, Japan and the Netherlands are the
major purchasers of Iranian products, he said, adding that the
value of petrochemical exports will be raised to 650 million
dollars by the end of the Iranian year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
