<HEADLINE> 2,000 Families Feared Trapped by Floods in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 19 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 2,000 families
are feared trapped in their homes in Nyando and parts of Nyakach,
Kisumu District in eastern Kenya, after raging floods partly
submerged their homes, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide food and medicines to the victims
and plans to evacuate them if the rains persist in the region,
Kisumu District Commissioner Ali Korane was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Overnight rains on Monday caused flooding on Tuesday and
forced residents to flee their homes. Property estimated at
thousands of Shillings, including livestock, household goods and
crops, are also feared to have been washed away by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, as the meteorological department forecast that the
torrential rains may extend into next year, it seems rain havoc
rises all round the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in north-western Kenya's Trans Nzoia and Uasin Gishu
districts, the hub of the country's food supply, stand to lose
their entire crop as maize continue to rot in the farms.
</P>
<P>
Western and central districts are the leading areas suffering
from high rainfall, with Lodwar and Meru stations registering the
highest of over 75 millimeters by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Coastal areas will also continue experiencing heavy
downpour this month, according to the meteorological department
here. About 15,000 slum dwellers in Mombasa, the coastal capital,
are threatened with landslides.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi, Kisumu and Nakuru received more than 60 millimeters
of rainfall respectively on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have so far claimed over 20 lives, with most
deaths occurring in central, northern and coastal provinces.
</P>
<P>
The rains and floods have been blamed on the El Nino
phenomenon which has affected the entire eastern African region.
</P>
</TEXT>
