<HEADLINE> Ukrainian President Goes to U.S. Over Chernobyl Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
today said the potential danger of the Chernobyl nuclear reactor
is more than his country's internal affair.
</P>
<P>
It is "an international concern," Kuchma was quoted by a
Ukrainian Inter-fax news agency report as saying here at the
airport before leaving for the United States.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, he would discuss the financial needs for
rebuilding the so-called "sarcophagus" on the fourth generating
set at the Chernobyl reactor.
</P>
<P>
The "sarcophagus" was hastily built up to cover the reactor
damaged in an explosion on April 26, 1986, which so far has led to
the deaths of 4,300 people.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, said the report, Foreign experts began to
throw doubts over the safety of the shelter at the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
The shelter was built "under tremendously trying conditions" as
a temporary solution, said John Holum, director of the U.S. Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of the shelter is estimated to cost 750
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven (G-7) leading industrialized nations has
agreed to contribute 300 million dollars, while the European Union
(EU) will provide 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government has decided to contribute 50 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The funding of the undecided 300 million dollars will be
discussed during a meeting with representatives from some 50
countries in New York on November 20, which Kuchma is expected to
attend, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma did not rule out the possibility of holding talks with
U.S. Vice President Al Gore over Ukraine's participation in the
construction of a nuclear power plant in Iran with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent unofficial meeting with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, Kuchma said there was not suspending
issues between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
