<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars To Help China Retrieve Dunhuang Relics (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Dunhuang scholars are
going to assist a campaign to try to get back some lost relics of
the Dunhuang Grottos in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Professors, scholars, and researchers from Beijing University,
People's University, and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
have decided to look into the question of how priceless relics
fell into the hands of foreigners. The results of the study will
be used as evidence in a campaign to recover Dunhuang relics that
have been brought out of China.
</P>
<P>
"It's been about a hundred years since relics were discovered
in the Dunhuang Grottos and Chinese academics are really concerned
about whether the relics can be brought back to China," says Ma
Shichang, an archaeologist at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, a Chinese Taoist priest found the entrance to a cave
in the Dunhuang Grottos that contained more than 50,000 ancient
books, sculptures, frescoes and documents on religion, ancient
science and technology, art, and literature.
</P>
<P>
In subsequent years, adventurers from Britain, France, Japan,
the United States, and Russia came to Dunhuang and acquired most
of the relics for next to nothing. Some people simply looted the
caves, and the relics can be seen in many Western museums and in
private collections.
</P>
<P>
Now, the Xiehe Group, a pharmaceutical company in Shenyang that
has donated money for Dunhuang research projects, has started a
campaign to recover the lost treasures.
</P>
<P>
"The relics can be best appreciated only when they are returned
to the grottos and kept together with the murals and frescoes,"
Prof. Ma told a forum sponsored by Xiehe Group last week at
Beijing University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars To Help China Retrieve Dunhuang Relics (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scholars attending the forum agreed that it will be no easy job
getting the relics back because it would involve complicated legal
and scholarly questions.
</P>
<P>
First, however, they will establish the true identity of the
"explorers" who removed the relics, how the relics were traded
away, and what the attitude of the Qing government at that time
was.
</P>
<P>
They also suggest that the government should support and even
lead the relics-retrieval campaign. They propose to first get in
contact with and negotiate with the relics' owners. Litigation
should be the last resort, they say.
</P>
<P>
The Xiehe Group's legal advisor, an American lawyer, points out
that there are international laws on the retrieval of relics that
were used to help Egypt regain relics from some European countries.
</P>
<P>
On October 9, eight books removed from Dunhuang were returned
to China by the son of a man who had bought them long ago from a
classical book shop in Tokyo. This was the first case of Dunhuang
relics being returned to China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Marts Closed Down for Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique government has
closed down sub-standard food markets to curb the spreading of
cholera, which has claimed 120 lives in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The move, started Tuesday, was announced by Aurelio Zilhao,
Mozambique's Health Minister, according to local daily Naticias
today.
</P>
<P>
The sub-standard food marts are said to be the main cause for
the spread of the epidemic disease in the worse-hit Maputo and
Gaza provinces in the country, Zilhao said.
</P>
<P>
He said the disease this time is more dangerous than in 1992
eruption, in that people suffering from it are getting dehydrated
in six hours comparing with the 24 hours five years ago.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 people have been admitted into the central
hospital of Maputo ever since the first case was reported in
August, he said.
</P>
<P>
The infectious disease is seen by local health officials as
caused by refugees from Tanzania and the Great Lakes Region,
Zilhao said, adding that the rubbish piles scattering around the
cities are also part of the reasons for the spreading of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The government is closing down the food markets, because they
are yet another cause for cholera, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the media and any other sector of the society to move
up for the end of the plague.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
