<HEADLINE> Vancouver Embraces APEC Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, November 18 (Xinhua) -- With the opening of the
media center here today, Vancouver is finishing the final touches
of its preparation for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) meetings scheduled to begin tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The media center, located at the Vancouver Trade and Convention
Center, will provide "working newsroom" facilities to the 3,000
journalists expected to cover the week-long event.
</P>
<P>
"Our commitment to ensuring that media have a first rate
facility from which to report on APEC meetings equals our
commitment to APEC delegates who will participate in the
meetings," said Robert Vandeloo, executive director of the APEC
97' Canadian Coordinating Office.
</P>
<P>
The media will have 24-hour access to electronic and print work
areas, briefing rooms, delegation press offices, translation and
interpretation services, telephone and facsimile services, and
computer support service in the 70,000 square feet center.
</P>
<P>
Colorful flags are flying high along main streets in the
bustling downtown areas, where hotels are packed, and restaurants
are more crowded and noisier than ever before.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more temporary "No Stop" signs have sprung up
on the sides of streets, making it difficult to find parking space.
</P>
<P>
The event, which is expected to attract a total of 8,000
government leaders, business and media representatives, will
surely cause traffic jams and delays to the Vancouverites.
</P>
<P>
This is "frustrating for driving people," yet, the general mood
here is "quite positive," said a Canadian media co-ordinator.
</P>
<P>
"It is a wonderful event, helpful to open new markets and
reduce barriers," he said. "Hopefully, it will be beneficial to
everybody."
</P>
<P>
But the political and business leaders here seem more convinced
that the event will be a plus to Vancouver, and Canada as a whole.
</P>
<P>
They see the APEC "as a sign that Vancouver is reaching its
promise on the Pacific Rim", said a report in a newspaper here.
</P>
<P>
It is generally considered here that the APEC will be more
significant an event than Expo 86, which is widely viewed as a
turning point that sparked international investment interests in
the city.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the event's success, leaders' safety in particular,
the city of Vancouver has mounted the greatest security efforts
that ever staged in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 police around the country are helping patrol the
city's downtown area. And, the Canadian military is also lending
its hand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
