<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Referendum Outcome Good For Hungary: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister
Gyula Horn said Tuesday that the outcome of the referendum held
last Sunday will do good to the country's future.
</P>
<P>
Horn made the remarks while meeting with former U.S. Senate
Speaker Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
The result, with 85 percent in favor of joining the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), will not only pave the way
for the country to join the Western military alliance, but will
also help its bid for a European Union (EU) membership, Horn said.
</P>
<P>
Hungary is expected to meet the EU's lowest criteria for
economic development by the year 2000 or 2001, he said, adding
that there should be no reason for further postponing Hungary's
entry into the EU.
</P>
<P>
Hungary was the only one among the three invitees to join NATO
that chose to hold a referendum, in which 49 percent of the
country's eight million eligible voters took part.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic and Poland, the other two invitees, also
welcomed the results, Horn added.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Hungary's relations with Russia, Horn said the
bilateral ties had developed positively instead of going backward
after the East European country sought to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Dole said the outcome of the referendum will help the
U.S. Senate ratify the eastward enlargement of NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
