<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection for Ancient Tombs in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- China's State Bureau of
Cultural Relics has recently decided to spend one million yuan on
protecting two ancient tombs in the Later Tang Dynasty
near the city of Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
The tombs were built in 947 and are rare in southern
China. They are in fairly good condition after more than 1,000
years, but suffer from water leaks in the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
With the aid of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, the
cultural relics department of Nanjing City and Jiangning County
will put a layer of cement over the tombs as a protective
cover and dig a drainage ditch near the tombs to reduce the
effects of water erosion.
</P>
<P>
They will also repair some sacrificial objects around the
tombs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
