<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Separation, Divorce Rates Rise in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Separation and divorce rates are
rising in Italy and the majority of separation requests are made
by women, the National Statistics Institute(ISTAT) said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of separations in Italy rose from 35,163 in 1985 to
52,323 in 1995 and the number of divorces from 15,650 in 1985 to
27,038 in 1995, the figures released by ISTAT said.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total official separations granted in 1995, 67.1
percent were requested by the wife and 63 percent involved couples
with children. Only 14.4 percent of separations were contested by
one of the partners.
</P>
<P>
The number of separations leading to divorce was, however,
relatively low, ISTAT added. By 1995, only 27 percent of legal
separations in 1991 had resulted in divorce, and 9.2 percent in
1992.
</P>
<P>
There would also appears to be a north-south divide, with more
marital break-ups in northern regions than in southern regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Invites Foreign Funds To Develop Water Conservancy Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwestern
China has attracted 338 million U.S. dollars in foreign investment
to build 14 key water conservation projects since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The province took the lead in attracting foreign investment for
building water conservation projects in the early 1980s, receiving
68 million U.S. dollars in assistance since then to develop
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The province long has been suffering from water shortages, but
officials say it has great potential for developing water
conservation facilities. The province's hydro-power capacity ranks
forth in the country, and it has used 21 percent of its total
water resources reserve.
</P>
<P>
With World Bank loans of 123 million U.S. dollars and a total
investment of 1.57 billion yuan (about 200 million U.S. dollars),
the project "Yingdaruqing" will divert water from the Datong River
to irrigate the arid land of Qingwangchuan. After the project is
completed in two years, 280,000 farmers in the region would be
able to rise above the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
The Jingtaichuan project to provide power and irrigation has
been partly funded by the World Bank and World Food Program of the
United Nations. The project has built 43 pump houses, irrigated
42,000 hectares of farmland, and attracted 280,000 new farmers who
chose to move to the region from other poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Guo Kun, vice-governor of Gansu, said the province will try to
attract more foreign investment to improve its water conservation
facilities and protect against natural calamities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, IMF Conclude Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) team which has just completed two weeks of discussions
with the Zimbabwe government on the country's macro-economic
policies said on Tuesday it had been impressed by the
government's determination to solve present economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said in a statement that it hoped the strong and
comprehensive measures adopted by the government would be a major
step in stabilising the economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that the stabilisation measures will facilitate
the release of balance of payments in the region of 100 million
U.S. dollars from the world bank and other donors," the fund
said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, the World Bank and other donors had suspended balance
of payments support to Zimbabwe's economic reforms after the
government, under pressure from the freedom fighters, bowed to
their demands to be paid pensions and gratuities.
</P>
<P>
The western donors said they wanted assurance that the payouts
would not further increase an already high budget deficit,
inflation and cause other macro-economic instabilities.
</P>
<P>
The discussions were centred on the need to stem the serious
foreign exchange pressures which Zimbabwe had been facing and
stabilise the economy in the face of large payments in pensions
and gratuities to former war veterans.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe government finally announced on Monday that it
would seek about two billion Zimbabwe dollars (140 million U.S.
dollars) on the market and freeze some recurrent and capital
expenditures in various ministries to raise about four billion
Zimbabwe dollars (280 million U.S. dollars) needed to pay the war
veterans pensions and gratuities.
</P>
<P>
On the same day the reserve bank increased the rediscount rate
by three percent from 25.5 to 28.5 percent and directed all
corporate foreign currency account balances to be offloaded onto
the foreign exchange market in tough measures to support the
Zimbabwe dollar which had plummeted alarmingly against major
currencies last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
