<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers In Central China Eye Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in the Dongting Lake
area, one of China's major commodity grain production centers, are
not hurrying to fill their empty stomachs but instead are eagerly
watching news programs on China's Central Television after a day
of hard work.
</P>
<P>
These farmers in central China's Hunan Province are encouraged
by the reported benefits of the Three Gorges Dam, the world's
biggest water conservancy project, on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River where the Dongting Lake is located.
</P>
<P>
Farmers here, who frequently suffer from severe flooding,
are optimistic about the future after the project is completed.
</P>
<P>
One such farmer recalled the disastrous summer flood of 1996,
which destroyed their dykes and inundated their houses and
fields. The flood overnight deprived them of almost everything and
caused damages of more than 30 billion yuan (about 3.7 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Once the Three Gorges Project is put into operation in 2003,
we will probably have little chance of suffering from flooding,"
the farmer said.
</P>
<P>
Dongting Lake, with an area of more than 2,000 square
kilometers, sustains 30 to 40 percent of the annual flooding of
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The river also deposits about 100 million cubic meters of sand
into the lake each year. In the past 46 years, the bed of the lake
has risen by 1.7 meters.
</P>
<P>
Through publicity of the local government, farmers also know
that the project is able to not only control flooding and
siltation, but also will provide water for irrigation in dry
seasons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Province Takes Water Projects Key in Bumper Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central
China plans to build water conservation projects in time to ensure
a disaster-free year, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Hunan's harvest this year topped 28.7 billion kilograms of
grain, up 1.8 billion kg over last year. The good harvest was
attributed to favorable weather conditions by local officials.
</P>
<P>
The province had experienced serious flooding in the last two
years. Water conservation work has focused on fortifying
endangered dikes.
</P>
<P>
This year, the provincial government called on localities to
make water conservation projects a top priority. After the autumn
grain harvest, five million people have been mobilized to complete
600,000 water projects.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is pooling three billion yuan (361
million U.S. dollars) to finish 600 million cubic meters of
construction on dikes, dams, reservoirs and related projects by
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, work has been completed on 219 million cubic meters
of such projects at a cost of 970 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Hunan expects long-term benefits from the present water
conservation work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
