<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Relics in Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have been
increasing protection of relics in the Three Gorges area after the
Yangtze River was blocked earlier this month for construction of a
power project.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing municipality and Hubei province, where the
world's largest power project is being built, have signed
contracts with 20 relics departments and universities in China to
jointly protect the historical sites in the area, sources from the
State Cultural Relic Bureau say.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,300 historical sites that will be inundated have
been put on a protection list, and 10 percent of the underground
relics and 30 percent of the tombs will be excavated as part of an
emergency program.
</P>
<P>
Experts have been preparing to move some important temples out
of the reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 relics belonging to the ancient Ba ethnic group
have been unearthed and are believed to be clues to understanding
the myths of the tribal society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
