<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Conference Approves Belt-Tightening Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The conference of the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO) passed the organization's
belt-tightening budget for 1998-1999 before its 29th session ended
here today.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural ministers and other officials who attended the
session also endorsed the FAO's TeleFood event designed to
increase public awareness of food and agriculture issues and
raising funds for a range of grass-roots development activities.
</P>
<P>
The FAO budget for 1989-1999 approved at the session is 650
million U.S. dollars, the same as that of 1996-97, effectively
forcing the organization to take belt-tightening measures.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted guidelines for surveillance and export
certification systems to harmonize plant quarantine standards.
</P>
<P>
It endorsed a program against African Trypanosomiasis, or
"sleeping sickness", a disease transmitted by the tsetse fly and
affecting a third of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan was admitted to FAO during the session, bringing the
FAO membership to 175 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
