<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Potential to Produce More Grain: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- China has virtually unlimited
potential to produce grain, said Yao Jianfu, an official from the
Ministry of Agriculture at a recent forum on the country's
agricultural development held in Changsha, capital of central
China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
A famine caused by grain shortages won't take place in China,
Yao said.
</P>
<P>
The actual acreage devoted to farming is 40 percent more than
the statistical figure, he said. Per capita grain production
reached 393 kilograms in 1990. Improvements in agricultural
technologies will also increase the grain output, Yao said. Though
some agricultural provinces, for example Hunan province, suffered
recent flooding, they still had a grain harvest.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country could face a shortage of feed. Eating
patterns of people have gradually shifted to meat, eggs, milk and
fish because their income has been rising.
</P>
<P>
Grain imports won't lead to increases in grain prices, Yao said.
</P>
<P>
Annual grain imports won't exceed 60 million tons by 2020, and
it would be easy for the world market to supply such an amount of
grain, said an economist from the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
