<HEADLINE> Italy's Transportation May Break Down in Jubilee 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 18 (Xinhua) -- An estimated number of 165 million
visitors to visit Italy during the Jubilee 2000 will stretch the
country's transport system to breaking point, the government's
official Jubilee agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the mass of tourists would need extra 20,000
coaches, 2,400 trains and 22,000 planes, Tourism Department head
Stefano Landi said the additional demand for transport would make
Italy's transport network look more burdensome.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he promised, efforts would be made to see that
transport problems do not become a disaster in 2000.
</P>
<P>
If the 165 million visitors do come in the year 2000, the
figure would be 28 million more than the total for 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Jubilee agency, set up by the Department of Tourism to
coordinate preparations for the Jubilee Year, predicted Rome would
be the most-attractive destination in Italy, which would attract
14 million tourist, staying for 53 million nights. 
