<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Try New Spin on Silk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Xishan, a city in
east China's Jiangsu Province, have created a new kind of silk --
color-weaving silk -- to overcome its fading and wrinkling nature.
</P>
<P>
The farmers who live in Caihuang village of Xing'an Town treat
the silk by a special process which allows the dye to penetrate
into the fabric and weave it into cloth, which improves its
resistance to sunlight, improves durability and resists damage
from washing and ironing.
</P>
<P>
The quality inspection center for state silk products conducted
a one-month examination of the color-weaving silk in July and
reported that the silk exceeds international standards.
</P>
<P>
China is considered to be a country of origin for silk and uses
the centuries-old method of weaving silk into cloth and then dying
it. 
</P>
