<HEADLINE> Road Mishaps Cost Bangladesh US$250 Million Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has an estimated
fatality rate of 58 per year per 10,000 registered motorized
vehicles, a rate some 25 times those of most industrialized
countries, according to an official report.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, this figure can only be an under-estimate as road
accidents and casualties are believed to be highly under-reported,
said a study published by the National Road Safety Council here
today.
</P>
<P>
The study also estimates annual accident costs at approximately
1 percent of this least-developed country's gross domestic
product, namely 250 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the annual number of reported accidents
has been multiplied since 1987 when a total of 1,521 road
accidents were recorded, in which 1,156 people died and 1,988
others were injured.
</P>
<P>
But in 1996, only eight years later, the number of reported
accidents increased to 3,727, almost 2.5 times that in 1987 while
the number of deaths caused by the accidents went up to 2,041 and
that of the injured people 3,301.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
