<HEADLINE> Space Shuttle Columbia Ready for Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for the space
shuttle Columbia's Wednesday blastoff finished today, said
officials with the United States' National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA).
</P>
<P>
The statement was made after a planned Monday launch was
prevented by a leaky helium umbilical on the launch gantry.
</P>
<P>
A multinational crew, on the 16 day scientific research
mission, will board the space shuttle, to be launched at 2:46
p.m. U.S. eastern standard time (19.46 GMT) from the Kennedy Space
Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle will carry equipment for micro-gravity experiments,
an ozone instrument and a free-flying satellite to be used for the
study of the sun's outer atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Columbia's crew include a Japanese, a Ukrainian and a citizen
of India. A spacewalk on the sixth day of the mission will be the
first by an astronaut from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The United States Air Force predicted a 60 percent chance of
fair weather for liftoff, but a weather system has forecast cloud
and rain. 
</P>
