<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Two Projects in Indonesia, Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
today a credit and a loan totaling 45.85 million U.S. dollars to
assist two projects in Indonesia and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
A loan of 34.5 million dollars will be used for Indonesia's
information infrastructure development project. The objective of
the project is to enhance the private sector's participation in
providing information technology.
</P>
<P>
The funds will also be used to assist postal and tourism
services by removing entry barriers, promoting access to
world-wide information services, and facilitating the flow of
technology and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Another credit of 11.35 million dollars will be provided to
help Bangladesh with a silk development project. It is the first
phase of a long-term program to increase the incomes of
small-scale silk producers, most of whom are poor women. New
technology, institutional and policy improvements will be
established.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries. 
