<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC to Continue Role as Oil Price Stabilizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) will continue to play a crucial role in
stabilizing the world oil price as competition among oil producers
becomes fiercer, former OPEC Secretary General Subroto said.
</P>
<P>
If OPEC was dissolved, a similar organization would undoubtedly
emerge because tight competition in the world oil market would
cause oil prices to drop, he told a discussion here Tuesday, the
Antara News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The discussion was held ahead of an OPEC conference scheduled
to take place from November 26 to December 1 in Jakarta. The
meeting will discuss the restructuring of OPEC, production quotas
and the selection of a new OPEC secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Subroto, Indonesia's former mines and energy minister, said
lower production cost of crude oil would reduce oil price because
oil producers would compete with one another for markets.
</P>
<P>
The condition would undoubtedly have an adverse impact on oil
producers, most of which depend on crude oil exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thus, OPEC would continue to play a crucial role because it
would set oil output in proportion to demand to prevent a decline
in the oil price, he said.
</P>
<P>
Oil price now stands at less than 20 U.S. dollars per barrel
against 34 dollars per barrel in the 1970s. The price dropped to a
record low of 10 dollars in 1986 because OPEC no longer functioned
as a "price leader."
</P>
<P>
OPEC members now supply nearly 40 percent of the world's oil
demand which has reached 73.7 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Subroto said there is no need for OPEC to push the world oil
price to 30 dollars per barrel but to stabilize it at 17 to 19
dollars per barrel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
