<HEADLINE> U.S. Bans Belgian Cattle, Sheep Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
banned cattle, sheep, their meat and many related products
imported from Belgium, fearing of mad cow disease found in the
European country last month.
</P>
<P>
"This emergency measure was taken to protect animal and public
health," said Joan M. Arnoldi, deputy administrator for veterinary
services at the Agriculture Department's animal inspection agency.
</P>
<P>
The mad cow crisis erupted in March 1996 when the European
Union slapped a worldwide ban on British beef after scientists
discovered evidence that a fatal brain-wasting disease could be
transmitted to humans from cattle.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is not a major meat exporter to the United States, but
the U.S. saw a 600 percent increase in exports of Belgian live
animals including cattle and sheep in the first half of this year
over 1996 levels, according to the Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
The United States has banned imports of live animals and animal
products from Britain, France, Ireland, Oman, Portugal,
Switzerland and the Netherlands since 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
