<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   U.S. Capital Losing Singles and Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Many single and poorer
residents are leaving Washington D.C. or consolidating households
to save money, according to a study.
</P>
<P>
The United States capital is experiencing its first decrease in
single-person households and households with annual incomes of
less than 15,000 dollars, according to the study released to the
District of Columbia Tax Commission today.
</P>
<P>
Demographer George Grier based his study on 8,537 interviews
conducted since 1994, and found that from 1990 to 1996, one-person
households decreased from 102,947 to 92,800 and two-persons'
increased from 66,926 to 70,900.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the district's population has declined steadily
from about 606,900 in 1990 to 543,000 in 1996, due to worsening
incomes, schools and crime, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Previously those leaving the city were mostly middle-class
families moving to the suburbs, but Grier said that's not the case
with poor people.
</P>
<P>
"They are not moving to the suburbs, that's for sure." Grier
told The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
A separate study on the city's homeless problem found that one
in every 200 district households requested shelter from May 1996
to June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The study, commissioned by the Fannie Mae Foundation, said a
preventive approach is needed to help families avoid a shelter
stay and to reserve that space for more acute housing emergencies.
</P>
<P>
One option would be emergency centers where families can go for
loans to pay back rent, the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0260 </DOCNO>
