<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank
President of Argentina, Pedro Pou, said the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) countries should adopt a single currency to lower risks
posed by speculative moves in international markets.
</P>
<P>
Pou made the proposal today during a seminar on financial
matters of Mercosur. The meeting was organized by the Foundation
for Latin American Economic Research.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of a single currency "is a long-term
goal and would represent the last stage of the integration
process."
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation for Mercosur's achievements, saying
that regional trade rose from four billion to 17 billion dollars
since its foundation.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, established in December 1994 to promote free trade in
the region, is the biggest commercial bloc in South America. It
groups Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. Chile and Bolivia
are associate members. 
