held on May 10, despite controversy over the presidential
candidate of the ruling Red Party, according to news reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The decision, said Vice President of the Court Alberto Ramirez
Zambonini, is based on a timetable approved by all political
parties of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramirez, all the political forces still have
enough time to solve their differences and register their
candidates, adding the deadline for the elections will "be as
scheduled."
</P>
<P>
The controversy within the ruling party arose when Lino Oviedo,
former chief of the Paraguayan army, was nominated presidential
candidate of the Red Party in the inner elections on September 7.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo's candidacy met with opposition from former Foreign
Minister Luis Maria Argana, who brought the case before the
Supreme Electoral Court by presenting an appeal for the annulment
of Oviedo's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
It was reported Argana alleged Oviedo was accused of complicity
in the attempted coup against President Juan Carlos Wasmosy on
April 3, 1996.
</P>
<P>
After the coup, Wasmosy had issued an arrest warrant for
Oviedo, but Oviedo evaded it by fleeing away.
</P>
<P>
In his defense, Oviedo denounced the plot that Wasmosy and
Argana concocted to prevent him from reaching the presidency of
Paraguay. 
