<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Agree on Justice Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Justice officials from both
China and the United States agreed here today that it is important
to strengthen cooperation in the battle against organized
international crime and illegal drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that cooperation and exchanges between legal
and judicial circles of the two countries would be beneficial and
necessary to both, Xiao Yang, the Chinese justice minister, said
after discussions with his U.S. counterpart, Janet Reno, and other
senior officials.
</P>
<P>
He said bilateral cooperation will also play an important role
in maintaining peace, stability and development in the world as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
Xiao headed a delegation from the Chinese Ministry of Justice
which concluded a three-day visit to the U.S. capital today. It
discussed in detail with the U.S. officials issues ranging from
fighting organized international crime, drug trafficking and money
laundering to cooperation in judicial research and the training of
lawyers and judicial officials.
</P>
<P>
"As the biggest developing country and the biggest developed
country in the world, China and the United States have better
opportunities and broad prospects for exchanges and cooperation in
the legal and judicial fields, despite their different concepts on
the rule of law and the legal culture," said Xiao.
</P>
<P>
He said cooperation would play a positive role in setting up a
Sino-U.S. constructive, strategic partnership facing the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived in Hawaii last Friday and left
here for New York City today. It is expected to leave the United
States for Canada on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
