<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Further Cut Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will
further cut the budget for the 1998 fiscal year, new Thai Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan revealed the plan to further slash the budget at a
briefing on the general military situation at the Defense Ministry
on Tuesday, local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said the cut was necessary because of an expected fall in
state revenues from taxes due to the current economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
All state agencies, including the military, will have their
expenditures trimmed in this round of cut, said Chuan, who also
holds the defense portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's government budget for the 1998 fiscal year, which
starts in October this year, stands at 823 billion baht (about 8.4
billion U.S. dollars at the current exchange rate), after the
previous government of Chavalit Yongchaiyudh made two radical cuts
totaling 159 billion baht (4.1 billion dollars) earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Thai Budget Bureau chief Seri Sathaporn said the government
anticipated a 22 billion baht (564.1 million dollars) fall in
revenues.
!! To keep the budget deficit at 1 percent of the country's gross
domestic product as set by the International Monetary Fund, the
government has to either raise taxes or further cut the budget to
make up for the expected shortfall, Seri said.
</P>
<P>
Since the government does not want to add any more burden to
the public, budget cut appears to be the only choice, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's state agencies this time are expected to be further
affected by the cut and they have to postpone or cancel more
projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
