<HEADLINE> World Crude Oil Demand to Rise in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- World crude oil demand in 1998
is estimated to rise by 1.7 million barrels per day (BPD), with
developing countries accounting for the lion's share of the
increase, an Indonesian oil official said.
</P>
<P>
"I see demand rising by 1.7 million barrels per day in 1998...
and from this total, 1 million barrels per day will come from
developing countries," Indonesia's Governor for the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) Purnomo Yuswantoro said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the projected rise in crude oil demand from
developing countries to the fact that these countries are
experiencing strong economic growth, citing China as an example.
</P>
<P>
The current world demand for crude oil is estimated at around
73.5 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The increase in demand next year may not necessarily be met by
OPEC, but by non-OPEC producers, local press reports today quoted
Yuswantoro as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 103rd OPEC ministerial meeting will be held here from
November 26 to December 1. A rise in both quota and price of crude
oil is likely to be a crucial topic of discussions at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
