<HEADLINE> Indonesia Enjoys Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's trade surplus is
expected to stand at 4.3 billion U.S. dollars in the second half
of the 1997-98 fiscal year ending March 31 next year, a cabinet
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad, in a written statement issued
Tuesday, said exports in the second half of the year would reach
25.788 billion dollars, including 21.354 billion dollars in
non-oil exports and 4.434 billion dollars in oil exports.
</P>
<P>
He said imports are expected to reach 21.479 billion dollars,
with non-oil imports amounting to 20.049 billion dollars and oil
imports 1.385 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that if the forecast is met, the total trade
surplus would exceed 9 billion dollars in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The country posted a trade surplus of 7.046 billion dollars in
the 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there are indications that demand for some of
Indonesia's export commodities has declined due to a drop in
demand in Indonesia's exports destinations as well as the failure
of the export products to meet standards set by destination
countries.
</P>
<P>
To resolve the problem, he said, the government will continue
to encourage the business community and exporters to improve their
efficiency and productivity while providing various facilities
needed to stimulate exports including fiscal and monetary
incentives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
