<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Rare Cranes Thrive in Nature Reserve(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Yu Zheng and Fang Fang
</P>
<P>
GUIYANG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Half of the world's rare
black-necked cranes are wintering in China's poorest province.
</P>
<P>
Caohai Nature Reserve in Guizhou Province is their yearly home
during the chilly winter months.
</P>
<P>
At least 450 black-necked cranes leave their usual homes on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau to wade through the grass and marshes of
Caohai, a 25-square-kilometer wetland, said an official from the
nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
According to World Wildlife Fund (WWF) sources, China has more
than 700 of the world's 1,000 black-necked cranes. The temperature
and environment around Caohai are suitable for migrant birds.
</P>
<P>
Tourists have been flocking to the reserve to take pictures of
the birds. Many rent small boats from local farmers to get closer
to the wading and swimming birds, especially the rare cranes.
</P>
<P>
"A great number of crane-lovers came here to see the endangered
bird, and some even took photos seven or eight meters from the
cranes," said Huang Mingjie, a program official with the Guizhou
Environmental Protection Bureau (GEPB).
</P>
<P>
"The work of farmers now would not disturb surrounding cranes,"
Huang said. "It is a very rare scene in any other place."
</P>
<P>
Caohai is a far cry from that years ago, Huang said. The
reserve had been nearly drained in 1972 to make way for more
farmland. Soil erosion, bad farming practices and outbreaks of
crop pests led to a decision by the provincial government to
restore the lake in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Black-necked cranes had dwindled to 35 birds, Huang said, but
the population increased rapidly after the wetland expansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece's Soccer Authorities Fined for Crowd Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Greek soccer federation topped
the fine list released Tuesday by FIFA in Switzerland at Zurich
with 75,000 Swiss francs (54,000 U.S. dollars) fining for crowd
riots at a World Cup qualifier.
</P>
<P>
FIFA made the sanction for Greek soccer authorities on watchers
of disruptions and fireworks at the October 11 qualifier against
Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Greece's soccer federation was also warned of further penalty
as a stadium ban for future problem.
</P>
<P>
Other decisions included Slovenia 15,000 francs (11,000
dollars) for same reason at another October 11 qualifier against
Croatia and Croatia 10,000 francs (7,000 dollars) for uncontrolled
fans.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian and Yugoslav soccer federations were each fined
10,000 francs for their violent fans.
</P>
<P>
Individuals bans and fines were also announced in FIFA's
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
A final decision on fan violence between England and Italy on
October 11 is expected on December 2, a statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
