</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Rare Cranes Thrive in Nature Reserve (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Yu Zheng and Fang Fang
</P>
<P>
Three years after the lake's restoration, a nature reserve was
established under the leadership of the environmental protection
bureau.
</P>
<P>
"Local farmers showed their resentment at the beginning,
particularly against the fishing ban there during the spring
breeding season," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20,000 farmers lived in the 96-square-kilometer reserve,
adjacent to the county seat of Weining, one of the most
poverty-stricken areas in the inland province. They survived on
farming and primitive handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
"We must care about the daily lives of the neighboring poor
people while running the nature reserve," said He Shicheng, GEPB's
deputy director. "We should help people there as well as those
lovely cranes."
</P>
<P>
The International Crane Foundation (ICF), Guizhou Environmental
Protection Bureau and the Trickle-Up Program (TUP), a non-profit
organization concerned with alleviating poverty, supported 412 of
the poorest farming families with grants and community trust funds of
100 U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have been encouraged to undertake projects that do not
damage the nature reserve or natural resources of the wetland.
</P>
<P>
Caohai Nature Reserve also chose 13 voluntary environmental
watchdogs among the farmers.
</P>
<P>
"So long as the farmers recognized that we care about them the
same as those cranes, they understand our work and the aim of the
nature reserve," He said.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is the most dangerous threat to environment, thus we
must find other alternatives to random exploitation of natural
resources."
</P>
<P>
Local farmers came to know that the wetland and birds would
also bring them profit. Expenditures from tourists to Caohai have
become the major source of income for the farmers.
</P>
<P>
In the slack season, 53-year-old farmer Wang Weide said he
could get more than 2,000 yuan (240 U.S. dollars) by renting his
boat to tourists, a huge income around Caohai. More than 40
boatmen like Wang benefit from tourism.
</P>
<P>
The ICF regards the reserve as a successful combination of
safeguarding cranes and human beings. The picturesque reserve will
be the host for an international conference near Caohai sponsored
by the ICF in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
