<HEADLINE> Civic Organizations Pledge Joint Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- About 30 national
organizations in the United States today pledged cooperation in
fighting drugs, promising to serve 1 million hours in volunteer
time between them.
</P>
<P>
Joined by the White House's drug policy director, Barry
McCaffrey, these organizations representing more than 50 million
people signed a civic alliance to work together on youth drug
prevention.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey emphasized the role of community groups in reaching
out to children.
</P>
<P>
Groups ranging from the Girl Scouts to Rotary International
promised their efforts, capping a three-day conference on drug
prevention strategies.
</P>
<P>
Participants suggested creating leadership opportunities for
youths, providing adult mentors and holding youth summits as ways
to spread the message.
</P>
<P>
Group leaders said the alliance reaffirmed the need for people
to fight together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
