<HEADLINE> France to Promote High-Tech in Schools, Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- France is launching a three-year
plan to introduce information and multimedia technologies in
schools, in an effort to promote new high technologies of the
country, said government officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will announce a series of measures to
encourage creation of enterprises specialized in new technologies
and will create a public fund for capital risk in establishing
such enterprises, the Minister of Industry, Economy and Finance
Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today.
</P>
<P>
The French Minister of National Education Claude Allegre
presented Monday a three-year plan to develop the use of new
technologies in schools.
</P>
<P>
The state will spend 1 billion francs (167 million U.S.
dollars) each year in financing equipments for the plan, whose
priority will be integrating information and multimedia with
primary school projects and training teachers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state will use 1 billion francs to be obtained
from selling the shares of the France Telecom to develop new high
technologies, with 600 million francs (100 million U.S. dollars)
to create a capital risk fund for such projects.
</P>
<P>
The government will introduce reforms in research institutes to
encourage researchers to set up enterprises with high
technologies, said Strauss-Kahn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
