<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Equities Rebound From Sharp Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Greek Equities rebounded today
on the Athens Stock Exchange with the general index closing 4.56
percent higher at 1,391.79 points and the FTSE/ASE index rising
4.48 percent at 809.13.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Greek equities suffered another blow from a round of
banking interest rate hikes and reports of a likely imposition of
a capital gains tax. The general index closed 3.88 percent lower
at 1,331.04 points, down 25.81 percent from its all-time high of
1,794.14 points two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Trading was moderate with turnover at 18 billion drachmas
(about 6.52 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Advancers led decliners by 187 to 37 with another 10 issues
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Banks rose 4.92 percent, insurance ended 2.64 percent higher,
leasing increased 3.57 percent, investment rose 3.84 percent,
construction jumped 4.14 percent, industrials soared 4.31 percent,
miscellaneous was 5.23 percent higher and holding increased 5.33
percent.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the increase to attraction of the very low
levels of prices and the dismissal of rumors that a new capital
tax would be imposed on share transactions.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here expected the stock market to stabilize around the
1,400 level after finding strong support at the 1,300 level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
