<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends More Warplanes to Gulf Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States will send
six B-52 bombers and six F-117 stealth fighters to the Gulf region
in an attempt to pressurize Iraq to reverse its decision of
expelling U.S. weapons inspectors, The Pentagon said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton also authorized Gen. Anthony Zinni,
commander of U.S. forces in the Middle East to deploy an air
expeditionary force of about 30 additional fighters and B-1
bombers to the region if necessary, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the B-52 bombers and Stealth fighters would be
accompanied by four KC-136 aerial refueling tankers and other
support aircraft. The armada would join some 300 U.S. warplanes
already in the region, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the Clinton administration decided to build up its
air force in the region because of Iraq's recent offensive
posture that threatened allied flights.
</P>
<P>
"We are reacting in part to a grave threat we spot in the
area," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
"What we have seen is extremely active activity by (Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein's) air defense system, more active today
than before he invaded Kuwait (in 1990)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said there was a lot of movement of Iraq's
anti-aircraft missile batteries on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"The offensive efforts, we say, are primarily directed at our
aircraft and that's what concerns us most," he added.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the warplanes in the Gulf was decided by
Clinton during his meeting with his military and diplomatic
advisors on Tuesday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Berger, Clinton's national security advisor, said
after the meeting that the beefing up of the American forces in
the Gulf region was "deemed necessary by the president."
</P>
<P>
He said the increase of the aircraft was a precautionary step,
not a signal that a military clash was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military already has a potent force of more than 250
Air force and Navy airplanes and 22 warships in the Gulf and Red
Sea within striking distance of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
About 150 of the planes are in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait and
another 100 on the aircraft carriers Nimitz and George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The George Washington, ordered by Clinton to move to the Gulf
from the Mediterranean last week, is currently moving south in
the Red Sea and will enter the Gulf later this week to join the
Nimitz.
</P>
<P>
The F-117 stealth fighters are little bat-wing planes that
fly at night and avoid radar detection. They dropped
laser-guided bombs with devastating effect against targets in
Baghdad and around Iraq during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
B-52 bombers were used during the 1996 strikes on Iraq to
fire low-flying Tomahawks missiles guided by computer chips and
satellites against anti-aircraft missile emplacements in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the six F-117s would be dispatched to Kuwait City
airport from their home base at Holloman Air Force Base, New
Mexico, and the six B-52s would go from Barksdale Air Force Base,
Lousiana, to Diego Garcia, in the Indian Ocean that is equipped
to handle long-range bombers.
</P>
<P>
Bacon also said if Zinni decides to send the additional 30
Air Force planes as an "air expeditionary force," they would
operate from a base in Bahrain in the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
