<DOCNO> XIE19971119.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Simitis: Greece Favors Gradual Rapprochement With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece was in favor of
gradually improving its relations with neighboring Turkey, Greek
Prime Minister Costas Simitis said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a foreign press association luncheon, Simitis
outlined the initial steps which he said needed to be taken by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
First, he said, Turkey must withdraw its claims to the
uninhabited islet of Imia and refer any claims it might have to
the International Court of Justice in the Hague. In return, Greece
would okay the release of the European Union (EU) financial
protocol, he added.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the question of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea could also be referred to the International Court of Justice
in the Hague, he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece backed Turkey's European orientation, he said, adding
that the condition was Turkey should respect European principles
and values.
</P>
<P>
He said that given the opportunity he would meet with his
Turkish counterpart, Mesut Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
During the first Balkan summit meeting in Crete early this
month, Yilmaz invited Simitis to visit Turkey and the latter
accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
Greek-Turkish relations have been strained for decades over
their disputes in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Currently, both sides are trying hard to improve their
bilateral ties, but no substantial progress has been made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
